\par }\pard \ql \fi-600\li600\ri0\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\tx555\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid4939102 {\f0\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033\insrsid4939102\charrsid15098283 I:\tab You were born in 1901?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And you stayed there until you were married which was 1923?
\par MC:\tab 1923
\par I:\tab You said that there were fourteen of you in the family?
\par MC:\tab Yes. There was.
\par I:\tab Where did you, come in the family yourself?
\par MC:\tab The ninth one I - I am, the ninth child. Yes.
\par I:\tab How many were boys and how many girls?
\par MC:\tab Four boys. Eleven girls. Four. No, I'd be wrong, there'd be fifteen wouldn't it.
\par I:\tab Are the boys older than you?
\par MC:\tab No, one younger. One younger and three older. And three - and - no, two boys younger, of course there was, two boys - oh I'm getting mixed up, two boys younger and one girl 'cos the - the last two have all died you see. Wel
l that left eleven really when me - me dad died. The eldest one of all - well I - I didn't know her. That died. I've heard my mother say. And then the - the last - the last two of all died, when they were babies, so that was really - well she had fourteen
 if you know what I mean but there's - eleven of us. Yes. Yes. In the family afterwards.
\par I:\tab And your father died in 1911?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes, 1911 when - I was ten. Yes. Poor old mother, she was left with all us. That was very very hard time I can tell you then t
hose times of day. There's no pensions or nothing - anything. No, we had a job to get what we did get and father was only a cowman. That's all.
\par I:\tab He was a cowman all his life?
\par MC:\tab All his life, and then died through drinking the milk from the cow. Yes, cos cow had got - well they didn't call it - TB that time, they called it consumption. And as you know they weren't as particular that time of day were they. See.
\par I:\tab Was he ill for quite a long time?
\par MC:\tab Oh over two years - before he died. Well then they sen
d 'em to this sanatorium home at Kent, well he was too far gone - then, and he was - wasn't down there a month I don't think and then came home and well less than a fortnight he died. Yes. That was terrible that - then. And I know my mother got - youngest
 was just four.
\par I:\tab How old was your father when he died?
\par MC:\tab Forty-six. Forty -six, yes.
\par I:\tab Do you know when your parents married?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, I think mother - I've heard mother say she was about nineteen. I think so.
\par I:\tab She was the same sort of age as your father then?
\par MC:\tab No, I think she was about two years younger - than my father. Two or three years younger than my father I've heard her say, yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Did they come from Broxted?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Both of them?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes, both of 'em from Broxted, yes.
\par I:\tab Had your mother ever worked?
\par MC:\tab No. No. No, 'cos she wasn't one of the strongest - and then she couldn't go out to work with all us children, she had to have someone to help her do the washing. Yes.
\par I:\tab Who was that then?
\par MC:\tab Well another lady - a woman in
 Broxted. Yes. 'Cos she couldn't get - couldn't do it. Well - you - you fancy, just one fireplace to do everything. Everything. And fetch water and all, you've got - got to - go right down there to fetch the drinking water.
\par I:\tab A hundred yards or so you mean or more?
\par MC:\tab Oh more than that. Yes. To go down and fetch it and come back well it was over ten minutes 'cos you'd got to fill - let the - pails down the well. That was a job I can tell you.
\par I:\tab Did she pay this person who came in to help?
\par MC:\tab 
Yes. Yes. Two and six I've heard her say, and then - if she could she used - they used to like a glass of beer, she used to give her a glass - beer for her lunch. 'Cos she was there from morning 'til late - quite late in the afternoon, teatime. Well when 
you do a lot of - I know they've been washing here seven sheets a day - at a time. And that's all by hand. There was no machines like they've got now.
\par I:\tab She came in once a week to do that?
\par MC:\tab To do that, the main washing you see. Oh well, it was terrible.
 And then - if you had - we used to have water butts outside to catch the rainwater, but they don't now because they don't put the piping round do they, not round the cottages. If you - that was empty - went across the road to dip it out of the pond. You 
d
id. We used to have a - little zinc bowl with a handle on, wooden handle on, and that go all this - green stuff on it, well you had to keep going like that - to - so you didn't get the green on it. Out of these ponds a side of the road. I - well honestly 
-
 the girls have often said we don't know how our mother coped with us because - no fireguard. No fire and the lamp stood on the middle of the table. Well we never did knock it down. But it - you hear of all the accidents now don't you. Not one of us ever 
got burnt, scalded or anything.
\par I:\tab Did you have to help in the house?
\par MC:\tab Oh we had to do certain jobs, yes, 'cos they had doorsteps and of course the very very old people used to call 'em grundsells. We used to have to scrub them with soap and water. Stair
s, you never had stair carpet. You had to scrub them down about twice a week. Tables. But honestly my mother - she was one of the cleanest women I should think in the village because she often got praise for that. Yes. And did all the needlework and all b
y hand.
\par I:\tab Did she make the family's clothes then?
\par MC:\tab Yes. I - well I - we used to have to sort of help her when we got bigger you know.
\par I:\tab You helped make the clothes?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Do little bits of stitching as she called it. Then they used to make these rug
s they used to put on the floor. Hearth rugs, I don't know if you know what I mean. Rag rugs. Yes, but - they used to cut about three pieces about that length - well, no, well cut no end of pieces but you got three pieces, you had one that way and one tha
t
 - and stitched them together. And then stitch them on the rug. Stitch them mind you with hand. And before you went to school some of us used to have to lay so many out on the table so many - on the old table so if mother got time to do 'em while we was o
ut she just used to do that, well we didn't come home to lunch - dinner.
\par I:\tab Would you sell those then?
\par MC:\tab Beg your pardon?
\par I:\tab Were those to sell?
\par MC:\tab No, mother used to put them on the floor, because the cottage was all - only ordinary little old red brick
s. Red bricks, you never had carpets, they had coconut matting. Fact is that - 'course the men used to bring all the dirt in from the farm fields, wipe their shoes on a sack, outside, never see doormats, I tell you, these young ones don't know nothing. No
,
 don't know nothing at all. And yet we thrived. I mean, mother never sort of lost - only first one that died was through vaccination. Yes, on the arm when that was eight months old. One sister died through the last war, never did know what happened to her
. My eldest sister died with a tumour on the - brain. And one brother died last - just before last Christmas. And that's all, the others are still living. So we hadn't done bad have we.
\par I:\tab What sort of a cottage was it, how many rooms?
\par MC:\tab Well little old t
iny cottage, one - one had only got two bedrooms. Well then when mother had all these children - the two cottages - close together, and the two front doors had - they belonged to a Lady Warwick - then, but he - he leased, and - and she had the two knocked
 sort of into together. So we had the two cottages made into one. Well it used to please us 'cos we had two pairs of stairs. It was - well they weren't rooms but there was a lot of tiny passages.
\par I:\tab So there were four bedrooms upstairs after that?
\par MC:\tab Three. See, 'cos one only had one. And one had two. We had the one in the beginning with two, but not the other one with the one 'til they was into - into one.
\par I:\tab But you remember that happening?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab It would be when you were about five or something?
\par MC:\tab 
Well they was made into - into two before I was five, because I know when I was four when me mother had the other little baby. When me - sister was born, that was right. See, the - girls was on the left, boys was on the right and me mother's went stra
ight through in the front. So I - I remember all of that.
\par I:\tab And then downstairs there would be two rooms?
\par MC:\tab Two rooms, and what they called a - a kitchen. Was nothing like - I mean, no fireplace, no anything in that. And then you had to go through this little passage to get to the kitchen. And it was all red - all these bricks.
\par I:\tab So you had quite a lot of room really after that?
\par MC:\tab Well - well - yet they weren't too much 'cos they weren't all them big rooms, you see, not in the cottages, and all us running about.
\par I:\tab Did you keep one of the rooms as a sort of parlour?
\par MC:\tab No. No, we used them sort of both but the - I remember the fireplace where we did sort of have meals. They had such great old big corners, 
you could get chairs up the corners, and they used to call 'em hobs. The big fireplace and right along there, corneas where you hung all...things. Yes, where we used to hang our Christmas stockings. And mother used to hang clothes up there to air.
\par I:\tab So there was a big fireplace?
\par MC:\tab Yes, well one -
\par I:\tab With a range in it you mean?
\par MC:\tab No. No they don't have those sort of fireplaces now, the - cottage fire where there's a little oven at the side with bars down the front, see you pulled - thing over the botto
m of the fireplace and the people used to set the teapot on there. Or put it on the hob. They never had it on the table like we do and put a cosy on. Never see a cosy or anything. No.
\par I:\tab You ate your meals in that room?
\par MC:\tab Yes. You see, 'cos when we went to school and we was tiny - I got older sisters, as we kept coming along the elder ones were bigger. Little ones had theirs - cooked meal at night and then off to bed. Half past five. Yes, half past five.
\par I:\tab Did you have to help look after the little ones?
\par MC:\tab Well I didn't 'cos I was - the bigger ones had like - see I've got six or seven more older than me. So I didn't sort of look after the little ones.
\par I:\tab But they did?
\par MC:\tab They did, they helped, you see.
\par I:\tab Take them out?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Oh we never went far, n
ot in the country really. There was nowhere to go. Well, my mother never allowed us out. No, not outside the gate. No. She used to go and pull great old big stinging nettles and put in the gate so we shouldn't go out the gate. Well she wouldn't know where
 
we were if we went out the gate, you - of course we'd got a big - yard - what they call a yard too outside and we had plenty of room to play. And a big orchard. Lovely orchard we had. So we got plenty of room - you know, when we went out, if mother allowe
d - allowed us out. But whenever went out - in the road - we run a bit wild after me father died, but that was - we used - that was when we were smaller. Yes. Oh dear oh dear.
\par I:\tab Did you ever buy clothes from a shop when you were small?
\par MC:\tab Well I - suppose
 now and again but not very very often you see. Mother - really had - she's so good with a needle. If one didn't fit one that'd fit the other. Well of course she had to buy a few I expect, and then we had to go to Dunmow to get them. Six mile. Six mile, t
he was the nearest doctor we had to go. Either Dunmow or Thaxted and three mile to the nearest nurse we had to go. I can't see the children getting up here and going to walk six miles to get a doctor now can you? No.
\par I:\tab You had to fetch the nurse when your mother had another baby?
\par MC:\tab Well the other sisters did, but I did when my sister - the oldest sister had a baby, she was home, my - mother said - we'll have to get up tomorrow morning Mary and go to the doctor's. That was me. I said, go to the doctor's? Y
es, she said. And - and they opened at nine. I shall never forget that as long as I live. Got up and went at nine and I said well what are we going to do if the zeppelins come over. I said, can I take a sack? She said, what do you want a sack for? I said,
 well I'll get in it. That was up top of Thaxted Common, quite a big hill because that's really straight they call it Thaxted Common, that time of day. But I mean -
\par I:\tab Why did you want to get in a sack?
\par MC:\tab Well I thought I would be out of the way of the ze
ppelins. Yes, I heard 'em say they was hiding when the zeppelins come over, and I thought, well what I've got to do. Well I mean I weren't very old - well I was thirteen. Thirteen then you see, when the war broke out. Well I weren't very big was I? Not to
 get up and go to Thaxted, six miles in the morning. Starting here at eight o'clock.
\par I:\tab Did your mother make any medicines?
\par MC:\tab Well the old fashioned - not medicines - well they used - what did they give 'em, some - oh - oh I don't - I forget what they cal
l it now. But I know she - they used make the old fashioned white oils if you had a cold, rub that on your chest. Have that, and that was - that was - good that was that time of day. I don't know how to make it. No. But - can't think of that what we had w
h
en we was children so good for colds. Not at the moment I can't. 'Cos they believed in onions didn't they. Onion gruel. Yeah. Yeah. Oh yeah. I mean you couldn't run to the doctor every time you got a little cold, not - 'cos he only had a surgery in the vi
llage twice a week. Tuesdays and Fridays, well I mean you - in between well you could die in between then couldn't you.
\par I:\tab Was there a sort of sick club for the doctor?
\par MC:\tab Well we had to pay in but I don't think - I don't really know how they went on not with the doctor that time of day.
\par I:\tab You don't remember if your parents paid for a sick club or a funeral club or anything?
\par MC:\tab 
Oh they paid in for death. Oh yes, paid in for deaths, 'cos me father never held with it. He didn't hold with mother paying in the insurances at all, until the little babies died - and then they got some money out and then he - he said, well I won't say a
n
y more. See? Because that did come in then useful to bury them with otherwise we wouldn't have had any money. Someone used to come round and collect that. Yeah. I remember that. Yes. 'Course my father was insured. 'Course it wasn't so dear that time of da
y was it as it is now. No. See us all trailing off to the funeral.
\par I:\tab What kind of a funeral did he have?
\par MC:\tab Well they had one - a horse drawn hearse that time of day with two horses. Oh yes. And we had to walk. Walk from one end of the village to the othe
r. 'Cos the church was pane end, we were the other. There's eleven of us without anyone else. And they all went, mother took 'em all. All of us.
\par I:\tab Was it just the family who went then?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, there's - 'cos we had no - a lot of relations as well. So I mean you get eleven of your own without the others. There was quite a crowd of us, yes.
\par I:\tab Did the neighbours come as well?
\par MC:\tab Several of 'em, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have a tea after that back at home or anything like that?
\par MC:\tab Well just a cup of tea or - you know, like they generally do, you know, just come in for a cup of tea, yes, I remember that. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember the neighbours and your relatives being sort of helpful at that time when your father died?
\par MC:\tab Well one lady was, well of course she's
 dead years ago, lived up the road, she - that was one what - who used to do the washing that used to come in and help my mother. Yes. Or when she had the babies, 'cos they didn't have nurses like they do now, they called them midwives. Yes.
\par I:\tab And she did that too?
\par MC:\tab She used to come in and help my mother, yes. They didn't make all that fuss then, like they do now. No. No. No, I got a sister you know as well. And she's got - she's - had twelve children. She's a widow and she's got - twenty-eight grandchi
l - children, and eighteen great-grandchildren.
\par I:\tab That was the one that you were talking about, that you went to fetch the doctor?
\par MC:\tab Yes, that were her the one, the one before that - older one - she - that was in all - she had one the same day as the wa
r broke out, I remember that. I had to go up to the old lady then. She said, I want you to go up the road - but that weren't the same one as - that helped mother with the washing, that was another old lady. Said fetch - this lady, tell her - tell her moth
er wants her. Yes. Well help - at that time of day you know was good, they used to help one another. More than they - really will now. Oh they did.
\par I:\tab Do you think that old lady that helped your mother really knew about medicine?
\par MC:\tab Well I was trying - bri
m - brimstone and treacle. That's something that - we had like that for colds, yeah. But - 'cos years ago you know there used to be these old people go around what they called gypsies, but some 'em weren't really gypsies and if you took notice what they s
ometimes - some of their remedies were very very - really very good. But whether my mother took any notice of them I don't know, but they wane, some of them, they were really good and they did help people a lot. They did and all. Yes.
\par I:\tab You saw a bit of them then as a child did you?
\par MC:\tab Yes. I know I was talking to one of my friends and I was - I was talking about that, well I don't know how you can remember it. Well, I said, you would if you had a life like we used to have. And yet we never went without fo
od, but to tell you it was a hard struggle to get it sometimes. But we never - never went really without. But how mother got it I don't know. No, don't know at all. No.
\par I:\tab What about shoes, how did you manage for shoes?
\par MC:\tab Well you see my uncle, my mother
's brother was a snob, as they called 'em. He - he used to mend our shoes. You see, 'cos we had 'em with tips and hobnails. Fancy a girl of my age having a pair of hobnail boots. Well they wouldn't look at 'em. Well you had to have something to walk to sc
h
ool didn't you. See. You didn't see so much of wellingtons that time of day did you, it's all - all heavy boots. Heavy boots. Men used to wear buckskins. You don't remember them I expect, no. Tell you, the farmhands - it is a good life. Really was a good 
life really. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father used to help at all in the house?
\par MC:\tab No, not in the house. He used to feed the chickens and do the cows, well that was a full time job you see.
\par I:\tab What if there was decorating?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, no, I don't think he done that, no.
\par I:\tab Or lighting a fire?
\par MC:\tab Oh he'd cut - only when they cut the hedges down. Nothing inside, no, didn't do any - 'cos they used to keep servants that time of day, and women to go in - live in to the work. No, he didn't do anything inside.
\par I:\tab I meant in your own home.
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Well they didn't do so much - at that time, they used to whitewash and - paper the walls.
\par I:\tab He did that?
\par MC:\tab Yeah, or me mother and - this woman what used to help do the washing, she would come in and do a little. Yes.
\par I:\tab Would your father make a fire at home or help?
\par MC:\tab What in the - indoors you mean?
\par I:\tab Yes.
\par MC:\tab Oh yeah, he'd go and lit the fire in the morning before he went to work. He'd got to light that to get a cup of tea.
\par I:\tab He'd make hips own cup of tea?
\par MC:\tab Own cup of tea when he could.
\par I:\tab Would he ever do any other cooking for himself?
\par MC:\tab Oh if mother couldn't do it, but you see she nearly always kept one of the elder girls home to help. 'Cos we grew all our own vegetables. Grew enough potatoes to last all t
he winter. Oh father did, in - in the allotment as they called it. Vegetables. Oh yes, we had plenty of vegetables. Turnips, Swedes and everything my father used to - well they did you know in the country. You didn't buy nothing. Well you had to buy the s
eed, but I mean you grew it - you grew it yourself. Yes. Ap - apples. Yes, we had lovely orchard. Plums. Yes. Then they used to make homemade wine. Yes.
\par I:\tab Your mother made homemade wine?
\par MC:\tab Well I don't think she made quite as much as some of 'em did but 
now and again she'd make a little. 'Cos - well I mean you had to buy sugar and all that for that. Couldn't make it without sugar. Then harvest time they - you'll laugh, because they used to get what they called the beer in. Little top - little barrels of 
b
eer, four and a half gallons. So that they'd got their drink during the harvest, 'cos you don't hear of harvest now. That supposed to have lasted a month. The harvest. And then they got - the - the - the bonus or something after the - for the four weeks. 
S
ometimes that took longer than that. Then they'd have one day out. Our men. To go to Dunmow - pay for the beer, pay for the rent, 'cos you only paid your rent once a year. Fancy paying your rent once a year, it was only about three or four pounds then. St
i
ll that - that was enough compared with the money you had. 'Cos I mean mother only had twelve shillings a week when I was born. And nine children. And you didn't get milk like they do now. Father used to come home sometimes with a can of what they called 
skimmed milk. Skimmed milk, well that - that was - welll you couldn't say it was water but I mean it wasn't - wasn't the best of milk. Other - other wise you wouldn't have had it. See, well - as I say they did make a - a pudding more or less. That.
\par I:\tab Would your father help inside the house with cleaning at all?
\par MC:\tab Well not when the girls was home. 'Cos he'd got enough to do on the allotment and that, that was a - well then in the - in the wintertime they'd be sawing wood up. 'Cos we used to have what they 
call faggots. Great old big - long pieces of wood like that that you chopped up to light the fire, well there's all that to do. And see about the children's shoes. Well anyhow I mean he didn't get home 'til half past five to six, well - especially in the 
wintertime, you couldn't do much then could you. No.
\par I:\tab Would he ever look after you when your mother was out?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. But she never went out. Not - not to say out. Not when we were young.
\par I:\tab She never went out to enjoy herself?
\par MC:\tab No, now and again she might go to church but I mean she never - never really went out. Well she`d always got a child - children to pull along with her.
\par I:\tab But you do remember him looking after you sometimes?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Yes, he's good in that way.
\par I:\tab Would he ever take you out?
\par MC:\tab 
Well, no, I don't think - no, we didn't really go far. No. No. He used to go to the market once a week to help the master. And that's where he used to buy our few sweets if he ever went, in the pony and trap. But - otherwise we never went - no, 'cos
 - I mean I - never went - we never even went on the train I don't think 'til I was about thirteen or fourteen. Well you - you - well you couldn't, I mean, you'd got so long - far to go to get one, three miles to the nearest station. And we got what we wa
nted in the little village. And the bakers come round. The butchers come round. So -
\par I:\tab You used to go off to buy things for your mother did you?
\par MC:\tab Go down the little shop. Well if she didn't - she more or less went her
self when she could. If not the - eldest sisters used to go. 'Cos I weren't really big enough to do the shopping then. Not then. And that'd be Saturdays 'cos the farm men never got - they used to get their money 'til Saturday night. No. Saturday nights th
e
y go their money. So if you wanted you had to go down the shops soon as you come home to spend it. Yes. Yes, Sundays and all I mean you went to work. Oh, yes, cowmen. `Cos they was only saying in - on the news or in the paper the other day, that's a full 
- every day the same, seven days - oh in the Archers, seven days a week, well it is. You've got to do it if you've got cows. You can't miss them one day. You've got to do the same thing every day the same.
\par I:\tab What was the farm that your father worked on?
\par MC:\tab Well they called it Wood Farm, Broxted, yes.
\par I:\tab How many people were there working on the farm?
\par MC:\tab I can't remember roughly but I mean there'd be the horse - they used to have horse keepers, used to do the horses, and my father and - well I suppose ther
e'd be a couple - two or three of 'em doing the cows, and then there'd be another one helping with the - poultry, yes.
\par I:\tab So quite a lot of men?
\par MC:\tab Well there was quite a few then, more then than there is now, yes. Oh yes. But - I must say that was an enj
oyable time, when that was harvest. Yes, that - that was when you go round see all these nice horses and - then we used to go gleaning and - the wheat, 'cos you could glean it and then that done for your own chickens at home, see. I mean you get your own 
e
ggs if you have your - if you've got a keep - 'cos we used to - there was a mill in Broxted, we used to go up and - I've been up many a time and - up from one end - end where we lived to the other end to get a quart peck of maize. Never hear nothing about
 maize now. It was all - yellow things they were and we used to keep picking 'em out eating 'em coming home. And those chickens food. Yes, they - you'll have to go up the mill and get me four peck of maize. Yes.
\par I:\tab What about going to bed, would your father ever put you to bed?
\par MC:\tab Well not really. No, 'cos - now, well we were bed you see more or less before he come home. Only Sundays. If me mother didn't put us to bed me elder sister used to put us to bed, 'cos we used to have to undress - downstairs in fro
nt of the fire. Poor old mum, mum sitting there. Come on, say your prayers. Put your head in her lap. We had to say our prayers. And then run through this passage, through the stairs with no carpets on, bed with a candle.
\par I:\tab What time would that be, about five?
\par MC:\tab Half past five. I suppose if that got about six we were late. 'Cos she'd got to prepare for the - the elder brother, cos they was on the farm you see. And me - and me dad. Cooking for them and the elder sister what was home for their - well then 
mother wanted a little recreation didn't she. And the toilet - was about as far as out down there, down the back garden.
\par I:\tab Did you have a big bed that several of you slept in or did you each have your own beds?
\par MC:\tab No, well - no we had a big bed, well whe
n you were small three could sleep in the bed, there was two big beds in one room for the girls. And the - big bed and and small bed one side for the boys, and mother and father's was in the front. Oh yes. But -
\par I:\tab How did you manage for baths?
\par MC:\tab We - didn't have one, you hadn't got a bath, hadn't got nowhere - we - we kept clean. Mother used to wash us down.
\par I:\tab In a tub?
\par MC:\tab I mean - yes, well we - in one of these old wooden - wooden wash tubs what they did the washing in. Oh yes, mother - was spotless -
 I mean we kept going without all these things what they've got now. We must have done mustn't we? Been alive so long, see. And funny enough you know, all my brothers and sisters, not one of 'em are dead. You generally get one don't you? In a family. But 
they're not, me eldest brother's still alive, he -
\par I:\tab Did your mother expect you - what happened if you got dirty when you were playing out in the garden, was she annoyed about that?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, we got to be washed.
\par I:\tab Was she annoyed about that though?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Made all that work. Yes, but - then we was made to mind. We knew we hadn't got to do things what she told us not to do, else we was in for it you see. So we didn't really do it - anything much wrong.
\par I:\tab What would happen if you did though?
\par MC:\tab Wel
l we - a smack bottom. Yes. It's never puts us - like some do, put us to bed without your sup - without your tea. 'Cos we hadn't had like really much all day. She never did that. Not put so we was hungry. We had our - our tea before we went to bed. No, sh
e
 never did that. If you put your feet on the chairs like they do, none of that, take your feet off them chairs, but - there's no - mother weren't cruel, no. Must say she weren't cruel at all to us. Of all the children she had. Beat when you've got a big f
amily, one helps the other, see, one helps the other. We used to sit down on the floor, and say well this is my house, another one'd sit up there and say this is my house. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Would your father ever punish you?
\par MC:\tab Well he - he - I only - I only re
member - hitting one of the boys, he'd got a - a prize apple tree standing on the right hand side in the front, and he was leaning him on that tree, that was a small tree, a special tree, and my younger sister went and picked one. He did slap her for pick
i
ng that apple. We remember that well. Because me father had idolised that, I don't know what he was going to do with it but it was a prize - but it was only a small tree. She went and picked it off. See. Yes. No. And then we used to have to clean knives. 
T
hey don't do 'em like they did now, used to have a knife board and used to keep on - cleaning like that, used to have some sort of brick dust. That was our - our job to clean - clean the knives. Well - I know I was laughing to my younger sister once, oh, 
I
 said, I'll let you see me book what I wrote. She said, I will when I come up. Remember when we did go to school we was little devils 'cos - if we got chance we used to be this here -rabbit wheat and of course they go ears on, they used to stick in their 
s
tockings and you'd say - you been up them stacks again? We'd say no. Don't tell more lies he said, 'cos I see the ears in your stockings. See, they gave the game away. But you say, as I say we didn't have so much freedom that we - we was like the other ch
ildren when we was coming home from school. Yes. So there was that. And then we - there used to be a brook - run across the road, you know, water, and then they went under the road and out the other - and we used to try and jump the brook.
\par I:\tab Fell in sometimes did you?
\par MC:\tab Yes. But -if we was too late coming - we didn't have to be all that late coming out of school 'cos you know how long it took us to come home from school, when we was let out half past three in the wi
ntertime, and we'd got - a good - over a good twenty minutes walk if you done it - straight - you know, come home like. But if you dawdled on the way that took you a little longer. Yes.
\par I:\tab But you weren't able to go fishing or anything?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. Nothing 
like that, we had a magic lantern I remember about twice. Up at the - 'course Sundays we was out practically all the morning, 'cos she made us go to Sunday school. Twelve to ten. And then from there they took us down to church in twos, we had to go - to c
hurch, so was out nearly all the Sunday morning while they was home cooking the dinner.
\par I:\tab Your mother didn't go to church?
\par MC:\tab Well she couldn't not with all us you see, the - 'cos they got to get the dinner.
\par I:\tab Would your father go then?
\par MC:\tab No, was out a
t work. He had to go Sunday mornings just the same. He didn't get a day off. Sunday afternoons as well. Yes, it's all work if you're on a farm really. You didn't have half days like they do now. You didn't get half a day at all, not even Saturday.
\par I:\tab You used to have these family prayers at home, that was just in the evening was it?
\par MC:\tab In the evening, when we -
\par I:\tab Did you have family prayers when you all sat down with your mother and father?
\par MC:\tab No. Made us - that's the time when we went to bed. Every night when we went to bed.
\par I:\tab Did you have grace at meals or not?
\par MC:\tab Well, they didn't used to say - they used to say - they used to say, for about what - what we're about to receive. See. Well that - that's what they used to say. If she had - sometimes we didn't because we had no time. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was there anything else at the church besides the Sunday school, was there a club or anything like that?
\par MC:\tab No. Well - only girls, they used to call it the Girls Friendly Society once a week and we used to go up the vi
carage and - do needlework or knitting or that, but the boys didn't go out. But the trouble was you see that it was so dark coming home. At night. I mean, no light. You didn't get no light. And then you went - from here to there before you come to a cotta
ge to see if there was a light in the window. It's dreadful to find your way home. See.
\par I:\tab Did your parents mind if you played on Sunday afternoon when you weren't in the Sunday school?
\par MC:\tab Well - we didn't go out much in the afternoon, this was in the morning.
\par I:\tab But did they mind if you played?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. No. Not if we could get out. Only in the yard - in - our - what you called our yard, we could go out there. Otherwise we'd be round there all the time wouldn't we. Cos by time they'd washed up, well that 
was easy about three o'clock and then - do the babies, whatever she'd got. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you used to have Sunday school outings?
\par MC:\tab Yes. In wagonettes. From here to Dunmow. Well that was a nice treat. Our school day treat we never went out, we just had it i
n the meadow. They did used to get a few swings what used to go with these old fairs. And a few races and that, but otherwise we didn't go far, not for everyday. Only Sunday school. Yes, we used to go to Dunmow.
\par I:\tab That was the sort of big outing of the year was it?
\par MC:\tab That was - that took - that took about a couple of hours, in these here wagonettes. But that was nice you know getting all these children sitting in the - in the wagonette. We used to enjoy it. Yes, then we used to draw one another about in 
an old sugar box. In the - yard as we called it. Oh we made our own fun.
\par I:\tab What sort of games did you play then?
\par MC:\tab Cricket, we only had a bat made out of a bit of wood and my father and they used to make a sort of a bat out of a bit of wood and - we - w
e used to have five marbles but we didn't always get the marbles, we had five stones, we used to sit down to what they called finks but don't have any of them any - we used to - spend hours sitting on the ground playing with these five - marbles if we got
 
the marbles, otherwise that was stones. But I never see children doing it now, or hopscotch. Between ourselves. Now and again perhaps she'd let - some other child come in and play with us, you know, but there was enough of us she said without having any m
ore. Yes. Yes. But after - I tell you, after me father did die - we - we went out a little more then. Yes, got out and about.
\par I:\tab Would you play then with groups of girls?
\par MC:\tab And boys, yes, got a little green just further up the road, we did sort of - 'cos she could see us out of the window see, we did - get out a little bit more then. Yes.
\par I:\tab You never had a bicycle?
\par MC:\tab Never saw one. Not even a doll's pram. There weren't them things when we was children. All the little dolls we had was about the - no hair, little black head, tuppence. That's all we had. But we thought the world of them.
\par I:\tab Did you collect anything?
\par MC:\tab No, had a spinning top, a kind of hop - hoop, boys had iron one, we had - wooden one. And a ball, tennis ball if we were lucky.
\par I:\tab Birds eggs?
\par MC:\tab Well you could only get them when you was coming home from school, you know, in the nest. But we daren't bring 'em home. We was like the other children, we - went in the he
dges when we knowed they was laying. Yes. Trees, I've been up many a tree. I wouldn't dare to get on chair now, let alone tree. No, used to be some little trees in front of our house - across - went across a bit of green and then the hedges went into the 
f
ields. We used to sit up there and moth - watch mother indoors. Slide down these branches. But we - made - I must say we made our own fun because we didn't have the things to play with. Not at all. We never saw kiddies bicycles like they have now. Nothing
. No.
\par I:\tab Never any concerts?
\par MC:\tab No. No. No, I never went to the pictures at all 'til I was eighteen. Eighteen when I went to pictures first.
\par I:\tab No theatre at all?
\par MC:\tab No. Oh no, nothing like that, no. No. Once you was in in the wintertime you never went out no more 'til you went to school the next morning.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever go out in the evenings?
\par MC:\tab No, he didn't go out in the evenings. No. No. No.
\par I:\tab Did he ever go to the pub at all?
\par MC:\tab No. If he want - if he fancied a glass of beer, if - if - could afford it me oldest sister used to have to go and fetch it. And - just had a glass at home, that was all.
\par I:\tab You didn't make the beer at home?
\par MC:\tab No. No. Didn't - didn't never make any beer at home. The only time they had it in was during the harvest. Yes. No, never made any beer at home.
\par I:\tab Did your mother make jam?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Make jam. We used to do pickles. Onions. Yes. Little onions. Well the people do now in the villages, do a lot of pickling of onions. Well they do round here some of 'em too you know.
\par I:\tab Did she bake her own bread or not?
\par MC:\tab No, the woman next door did. Woman next door, 'cos used an old-fashioned bake house - for the two cottages. You see, well that's three really 'cos that used to be three where mother was, well then there's anothe
r - another one joining it so it was like the three cottage and in the end there was two, but the - this bakehouse shared all the three. Well this other - never used to come - round the back way, and the bakehouse was sort of in be - in the middle of thes
e cottages if you know what I mean. She used to bake every week. Lovely bread. And we used to run home from school when we knew she was baking.
\par I:\tab You had to pay her for that?
\par MC:\tab No, she'd give us a huffa. Yes, 'cos she hadn't got no children. She'd give us a huffa. Half a huffa. You see, when you bake the bread you can put all - you can cook your dinners in the hot oven.
\par I:\tab She would cook a dinner for you too then?
\par MC:\tab Well mother - she - if mother'd got it ready, if she'd got a pie or anything - she'd say, I'm finished now if you like - if you'd like to come and put your pie in there. Yes, after she'd finished with the bread.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me what a typical day's meals would be?
\par MC:\tab What with us?
\par I:\tab Yes.
\par MC:\tab What - have a cooked meal you mean?
\par I:\tab What about breakfast in the morning, what did you have to eat usually on a typical day?
\par MC:\tab Oh we had - bread and butter or something like that, bread and jam, that's what we used to have, we didn't have cooked breakfast, no. Then we had to take - bread wi
th us for lunch at school. Didn't get nothing to drink unless you had a little water for school. Then come home then we had a - full dinner.
\par I:\tab That was the main meal?
\par MC:\tab Yes. We used to have suet puddings, I mean that was - that was better food then than what it is now. But - suet and the flour and all was better than what you get, now isn't it. Well I don't know whether you've heard people say but it is.
\par I:\tab And vegetables with it?
\par MC:\tab Potato - oh yes, potatoes and greens. Yes. We had goad meal before we went to bed.
\par I:\tab Your father would eat separately from you would he?
\par MC:\tab Yes, at the night 'cos we was in bed you see. Yes. Afterwards.
\par I:\tab What about midday, what did he do then?
\par MC:\tab Well sometimes if he was near he'd come home, otherwise they had to take their dinners, the men did.
\par I:\tab Did he have a cooked breakfast?
\par MC:\tab Well I shouldn't - we used to be at school.
\par I:\tab You don't remember?
\par MC:\tab No, well you see we'd be gone to school just after half past eight and I don't think, he'd come in 'til nine. Perhaps he had a piece of fried bacon or something like that. But we never.
\par I:\tab Do you feel that after he died that you had less food or not?
\par MC:\tab Well we did because mother got - I mean mother had such a struggle to get it.
\par I:\tab What difference did it make, did you eat less meat for instance do you think?
\par MC:\tab Well - never really did have a lot of meat you know, 'cos she'd make what I - we called a great - a big meat pud - pudding, well there was more pudding than there was meat and so - well then she'd make one of they
 - perhaps we didn't have meat one night, she'd make one of these great old big - plum puddings. But of course the plums then were better than what they are now, because you had to stone those sort of plums which - which people used to say were grapes but
 
I don't know whether they were or not but anyway they - but they really was lovely. If you cut a slice of it it'd he about half as big as that. Well now, you got one of those that filled you you see. Yes, we never went about hungry. No, never went about h
ungry.
\par I:\tab Do you think your mother had less food so that the rest of you could have enough?
\par MC:\tab Well I dare say she did go without sometimes you see to let the children have it. Well really we - she had hers after, we - we really didn't know what she was eating. No.
\par I:\tab Would she cook this suet pudding once a week then?
\par MC:\tab No, nearly every night we'd have a pudding. Something to fill us. After having bread all day, we'd have - have this - suet pudding in the night. And greens. Potatoes.
\par I:\tab What about the eggs?
\par MC:\tab Well we got eggs.
\par I:\tab When did you have those?
\par MC:\tab Perhaps we'd have one of them for tea, I - I don't think we had any for brea
kfast, no, we didn't - we didn't have any - any for breakfast. I'm sure we didn't, only just bread and - butter or bit of bread and jam, whatever we wanted before we went to school.
\par I:\tab You didn't keep a pig?
\par MC:\tab No, me father never. No, no, I don't think h
e kept a pig. No, he didn't. Me brothers kept one after - of - well - they were married and kept one, but I don't think my father had. 'Cos he used to get a rabbit or - up the farm. My father did. And - rabbits - yeah, well the rabbits that time of day we
r
e - were delicious, I mean there was nothing what there is now about. We got a rabbit and mother got a - a little piece what she called fat - well it weren't all fat, and then bake it, that really made a - a - a really splendid dinner that did. Then - Tue
sdays there used to be the bacon fat come round from Dunmow, with - fr - liver and all that sort of thing, Tuesday nights, and then - that was too late for us so she had ours Wednesdays. Wednesdays for our tea. See?
\par I:\tab Did she make a soup sometimes?
\par MC:\tab Soup? Oh yes. Soup. Yes. Onions and carrots and - dumplings and - and that would be another change. Stew they called it didn't they. Yes, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever have any tinned food like corned beef?
\par MC:\tab No, there wasn't so much of that stuff about then as
 there is - oh no, that was all - you go and buy, you didn't buy tinned food. I never used to see the tinned fruit much then. No. It's only these last few years that's come - these years that's come out. You ask some of the other older ones, you didn't ha
ve that tinned stuff. I know they had it in the Army, called it bully beef didn't they. Yes. Yes, called it bully beef. Yes. No.
\par I:\tab Did you all sit round the table together or did you take turns?
\par MC:\tab Well you see, at night we'd had ours.
\par I:\tab When the children were having tea, would all the children have it together?
\par MC:\tab Yes, sit round the table, 'cos I mean she'd got a large table. There'd be about three or four, six one side, and two - the narrow end and - see. Oh yes, we managed quite well like that, one of these great big white tables that you scrubbed.
\par I:\tab Your mother would serve you the meals?
\par MC:\tab Yes. And the elder sister. See they both done it together.
\par I:\tab Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par MC:\tab Well you could say a few words but - you had to be pretty quiet. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was the baby at the table as well?
\par MC:\tab No, well that used to lay in a chair. But - well until you see my father died then we - of course we got bigger and we didn't - have any babies then but - no, we all sat up the table. You didn't have to sit anyhow.
\par I:\tab You had to sit upright did you?
\par MC:\tab Yeah, we had to sit - and sit up to the table. Yes.
\par I:\tab What about holding your knife and fork?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, knives and - yeah, we always seemed to - have a special ones, one'd say, well that's my knife. You've got my fork. Yes. Well I couldn't - didn't know the difference but they did, we - seemed as though we knew the difference. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you each have your own chair then?
\par MC:\tab No. No, the chairs was all - practically all the same.
\par I:\tab You always sat in the same place though?
\par MC:\tab More or less. More or less sat in th
e same place. And we all had our own - mug. Not cup and saucer but a mug. Oh yes, we - we were treated properly and mother always had a nice white tablecloth on. Yes. I'm not going to say it was a bought one but people that time of day used to buy the - m
aterial and make them. Oh yes, we - we didn't have it anyhow.
\par I:\tab Could you ask for more if you'd finished?
\par MC:\tab If there's some left, if we hadn't had enough. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did she say if you didn't finish what she gave you?
\par MC:\tab She'd say, you can eat all tha
t up, eat that all up, she'll say, tonight. But more or less we did eat it I mean 'cos we weren't dainty and - the food was cooked well and - tell you what mother used to make and - we all used to enjoy them, was apple - we
\par I:\tab I suppose there wasn't any choosing between food was there?
\par MC:\tab We had to eat what mother got. Yes, what mother give us you see.
\par I:\tab What about at the end of the meal, could you leave when you finished or did you have to wait 'til everybody had finished?
\par MC:\tab Well wait 'til they were al
l finished and then get down from table. And then we had - she say, now go and wipe your hands. Well she'd say wipe 'em because the water was through the other place you see, the - and if - if it was very very cold you had to take the key to get - the hot
 water, 'cos you'd got no hot water. Couldn't get down from table 'til we'd wiped our hands, they were sticky, you see, that's right. Can't see 'em doing it now. Oh no. No.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me about the ideas, your ways of behaving? How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par MC:\tab Oh you - we had to behave. Oh yes. Well we - we did behave because we knew we'd got to do it. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did they say was important in life to you do you think in bringing you up?
\par MC:\tab What - strict you mean?
\par I:\tab What sort of things did they say were important in life when they were bringing you up?
\par MC:\tab Well to keep - keep clean and - don't in tell such lies and - anything else like that, see, that's the way, yes. But we - we - we - we never. No. Oh we had good reports when we went to school. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of people do you think they hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par MC:\tab Well I expect they hoped us that we'd turn out all right, I don't think any of 'em turned out too bad all - really at all. I had one broth - a brother, the la
st brother that died just before Christmas, he was a bachelor, well he was seventy-three. He went in the First World War. He was all right 'til he went in the First World War and then somehow or other - the war just sort of turned him, he wasn't - he - yo
u
 couldn't call him silly. He weren't silly, he didn't go in a mental home. But he went in a home, for the rest of his life, and there he stayed. See. That was the only one. Yes. And that was through going in - in the Army. Things didn't turn out quite as 
they should do, and he wouldn't - wouldn't work and - and see mother couldn't afford to keep him, and he wouldn't get up and - one like that. Anyway -
\par I:\tab They brought you up to work hard did they?
\par MC:\tab Well they had - see my brothers went on a farm. There's 
nothing else really much in the village they could do. Not that - not then. You never heard of - many people going further afield to work, not if there was a - well they were just brought up to do the - farming you see. 'Cos I've - still got a brother on 
there now, on the farm.
\par I:\tab Did they expect respect from you would you say?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Were you allowed to talk when other grown ups were talking?
\par MC:\tab No. No. No. She said, did you hear what I say? Yes. Little children should be seen and not heard. That - that was what we got, little children should be seen and not heard. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you find them easy to talk to?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, yes, mother was. We used to like to hear her sit and sing hymns. When she got five minutes.
\par I:\tab She was easier than your father really would you say?
\par MC:\tab Well you see - actually me father weren't home long because he was always at work, we never seemed to got the chance to be with me dad a lot.
\par I:\tab So really your mother was the one you got most of your ideas from?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. 'Cos as I tell you, me dad - we had to go to bed and we only saw dad Sunday afternoons. 'Til the end I mean. As I said to you, he was home two years before he died.
\par I:\tab He was home all that time?
\par MC:\tab All that time. All that time. And funny eno
ugh - the TB started in his foot. Started swelling out. Then we'd got a little piece of green - opposite our house, you went down the yard, crossed the road and this piece of green, he used to sit there for ho
\par I:\tab That was more recently though, not at the time?
\par MC:\tab Well they said that me dad sort of was - got it when he - before they were born. So they de - they developed it straight away you see, they wouldn't have lived, if they'd have lived they said they would have -
\par I:\tab That's why they died?
\par MC:\tab Yes, wel
l they said if they had have had to have lived they would have sort of been a backward child. Well, one child - the first - of the last ones - they - they was both little girls, died at ten months. Well then - mother had the other one, there was only - 1 
year in between, or a year and a few months, and the other one died, the last one died at ten months. Both of 'em - but they weren't - not together, but they was both - both ten months old. See?
\par I:\tab If you had any worries as a child could you talk to your mother about them?
\par MC:\tab Well yeah, but they - it - you sort of talked to 'em, but they - they didn't talk to you like - the mothers talk to their children's these days. We didn't - if - we sort of had to learn it the best way we could. She wouldn't tell you a
nything. No. No, she never told you anything. The children know more now - before they're left school than I did when I was eighteen. No, she never - well they didn't that time of day, they never seemed to - tell you any troubles or - tell you anything wh
at was going on, not really. Not if they thought you weren't old enough to know. No.
\par I:\tab Would you say she showed affection?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. There couldn't have been a better mother. No. Oh no, couldn't - we couldn't have had a better mother. No. We couldn't hav
e had a better mother at all, not all us children. And I know me and my sister - now, we're - well I - I - I - well I don't know do you Mary, she'll say, how mother did cope with us all.
\par I:\tab It's amazing?
\par MC:\tab That is. And - and - got to fetch every drop of 
water you want, and now you can go to a tap, switch a light on. Yes, we had - she had to fill the lamps, get the candles. Go to bed with a candle. Oh that was terrible hard work if - that was. What it i
\par I:\tab Wholesome anyway?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did they think about swearing?
\par MC:\tab Well, we never - we didn't swear. No. If me father - and he didn't swear in front of us. We weren't brought up to swear, no. We might - mother might say dammit. Or if anything went too wrong blast it, but I - as far as that, I
 never heard her and I don't swear. I don't swear at all. If anything goes wrong I never swear. No. It don't appeal to me. 'Cos I know my husband sometimes would - well he was very bad in that before he died, and I'd say, now what good's that done you? No
, I don't believe in swearing. But they - you don't get no further. Do you? No. I have felt like some people sometimes, but then I never do. I just say, oh damn it, what I have done now, and that's about - that's - no - no.
\par I:\tab When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par MC:\tab Well no, perhaps he'd give us a few extra sweet and that but we didn't get much. Might have given us perhaps a penny to go down the shop. But it didn't make all that lot - a lot of difference you see, she couldn't gi
ve one anything much without the other, as there's so many of us so it didn't really make a lot of difference. No.
\par I:\tab You didn't have any special food or anything?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. No. No. No. No, didn't make - didn't make a great deal of difference at all, as I say we might have had extra penny.
\par I:\tab Did you have pocket money usually though?
\par MC:\tab No. No, never had no pocket money. We used to go to school sometimes she'd give us a farthing. We used to spend a farthing. You got more sweets then in - farthing than you
 do for a shilling now. No. We never see a firework. Never saw a firework when I was a child. No. Never saw a firework. No.
\par I:\tab What about Christmas?
\par MC:\tab 
Well we used to - hang stockings as I tell you round this corner. We did get a orange. We used to be great old big - Christmas sweets that time of day, mice, little mice, I don't know, you might have seen them, the old mice. Apple. Or - something differen
t in a little bag. Put something in just to sort of three - for those long stockings, three parts fill your stocking, just to let you know that was Christmas. But we had plenty of food. That was the main thing wasn't it.
\par I:\tab Plum pudding?
\par MC:\tab Yeah, a huge on
e at that. She used to cook it the day before. 'Cos it - well you couldn't have got it on our one fireplace. And you couldn't make puddings in a basin 'cos you would - you wouldn't have large basins would you. For all us. I should think they'd be about - 
m
ore than half bigger than that table, pudding, the slices - would be come across - if you got a bread knife that'd be the width of that. Cut a slice. They real - they really was lovely puddings. People used that time - that time of day toast 'em in front 
-
 a slice of it in front the fire when it was cold. I wouldn't mind if I cold go and get some of it now sometimes. 'Cos that was real suet. 'Cos the box suet ain't - ain't the same as the suet what they used to buy and chop up. Seen my mother - stand there
 with a knife, get it - chop it up little suet. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were there any special games in the family at Christmas?
\par MC:\tab No, used to play snakes and ladders or ludo and - them sort of games between us like. We didn't - go bed perhaps quite so early the Christma
s night or night before Christmas. Just to let us know that was Christmas 'cos we weren't going to school the next day.
\par I:\tab Did your mother and father join in the games or not?
\par MC:\tab Well, sometimes she'd have a game of snakes and ladders but - just for a little peace and quietness. No. Father always be there. Always used to sit and -
\par I:\tab You were saying about your mother singing hymns?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes, used to sing hymns to us. Well say - if it was Sunday, but other days she'd sing a little old fashioned song. Yes. Which was rather nice. Yes, we used to like it, we used to say, come on mum, let's - will you sing a little song.
\par I:\tab What sort of a song was that she sang?
\par MC:\tab Don't Go Down the Mines, Dad'. That's one of 'em. And 'Jimmy Me Own True Loved One', well they were really old fashioned songs they were, and then hymns. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was she the only one who sang in the family?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, me brothers and them used to sing but we used to like to hear mother sing as well you see. Yes.
\par I:\tab So you'd all sing together sometimes?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Have a little hymn.
\par I:\tab Did anyone play an instrument?
\par MC:\tab We hadn't got any. No. Only a mouth organ.
\par I:\tab Who would play that then, one of the brothers?
\par MC:\tab My older brokers used to play a mouth organ, that used to be a craze that time of day. They thought they was well off if got a mouth organ. Oh no, we hadn't got nothing else. No. No.
\par I:\tab Did you have any books in the house?
\par MC:\tab Oh yeah, we had several books. Yeah. To - to read, you know. Well only children's books. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you see your mother and father reading?
\par MC:\tab No. No. We could - didn't get newspapers only once a week. Once a week.
\par I:\tab Do you remember what that was?
\par MC:\tab Yeah, 'News of the World' Sundays. And then we used to get - the Essex Chronicle once a week. That comes from Chelms
ford doesn't it? You seen it? Oh. And - and that is Colchester and all that news in round that way. Yeah. I have that, mother used to have that. So I get all the Essex news in it round that way. Yeah, I used to get that once a week on a Friday, but that w
as all, you know, 'News of the World' on a Sunday.
\par I:\tab You didn't have any family magazines?
\par MC:\tab No, only the church parish magazine, we used to have that. Yes. Yes, had the parish magazine. But - no, there was nothing else do
ing. There was no clubs or anything that time of day that going to, like there is now, the over sixties and that, there was nothing of that then. No.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go out to visit relations?
\par MC:\tab Well our auntie sometimes 'cos we used to go up and take the shoes to be mended, up me - uncle's - was a shoe repair. And nearly every night there'd be someone's shoes to take up to have something done. Yes. Auntie. Yes.
\par I:\tab What about Bank Holidays, did anything happen then?
\par MC:\tab No, only August Bank Holiday we use
d to have a - what they called a flower show at Eastern Lodge and that really was a good day that was. We took everything to put in the show. That - we did go there. Yes. Mind you we had to walk. Oh yes. That, took us about three quarters of an hour to wa
lk. Yes.
\par I:\tab Would Lady Warrick be there?
\par MC:\tab Yes. That's been years ago because the - the place is all - pulled down now. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you see much of Lady Warrick?
\par MC:\tab Yes, 'cos she used to come to mother's 'cos you see - if you did - weren't able to t
ake the rent she used to come and collect it. Yes, then we used to go up - up - about once a week, she used to sell lovely dripping. 'Cos it was dripping. We - mother used to say, go up - up the Eastern Lodge, and get some dripping. She used to sell it qu
ite cheap. Yes. Oh I think mother done some what they call fancy stitching for her. Yeah. Well they don't do it now on - canvas sort of work, where they done flowers. That sort of stitching.
\par I:\tab Was she a help when your father was ill?
\par MC:\tab Don't - really know.
\par I:\tab You don't remember that?
\par MC:\tab No, I don't really know, no. But - I mean she was a lady, but yet she wasn't a lady to talk to you, she'd talk to anyone, rich or poor. In fact I think she talked to the poor as - more than she did the rich in a way. She'
s one of those sort of ladies. Yes. Oh yes. 'Course she's dead now. Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par MC:\tab No. No. Never heard nothing about a hol - a holiday. I don't think me mother come from a very big family. No, she - well her - I've 
heard her say her mother married twice, this uncle what used to do our shoes was a stepbrother. And she had a stepsister but I don't think she'd - she'd - there was only her - with the one parent, but the other two was step - stepbrother and stepsister, t
hat's all I can hear us talking about. See. But her mother had a very hard life - I've heard her say.
\par I:\tab How was that?
\par MC:\tab 'Cos her - me mother's father - used to drink - in the village you see. And I've heard her say that - her mother had a - a very hard life with him when she was younger. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother take any interest in politics?
\par MC:\tab No, I don't think so. No. You - you didn't - hear much in - in the little village talking about 'em, no, they used to vote when there's any voting come round but -
\par I:\tab Do you remember your father voting?
\par MC:\tab I don't think he went, I can remember vote - I can remember the voting coming to our little school once when, I was a little girl.
\par I:\tab But he wasn't interested in politics?
\par MC:\tab I don't - I don't think he wen
t because I mean he - he - he wasn't home from work time enough and it was a long way to go. I don't think he ever went. Sure he didn't. No. No. I remember we used to wear the different colour ribbons. Like we did the Oxford and boat Cam - race, but they 
don't do that now do they. No. No. Yes.
\par I:\tab On Sundays did you have to put on special clothes?
\par MC:\tab Well, we had a better - we hadn't got all that special but - we kept a - special - well - like a good dress to go out in on Sundays. She never let you wear it 
out anyhow. Oh no. I don't think we got all that amount of special things. They was always washed and - and so nice that - we all sort of really looked nice in a way. Until me father died, and then we - had us in black frock.
\par I:\tab You had black, you put on black did you?
\par MC:\tab All black.
\par I:\tab All of you?
\par MC:\tab Well they used to that time of day, nobody never went out - to a funeral unless got black.
\par I:\tab How long did you go on wearing that for?
\par MC:\tab Oh they - they always reckoned for nine months - for the shortest. Then we wore em 'til we wore 'em out. Yes.
\par I:\tab It must have cost a lot to get you all fitted up like that?
\par MC:\tab Well it did because I - I remember the - the - afterwards you see they coming r
ound before mother could get any help towards us after father died, she had to show all these bills, what everything cost and all. See, see if she'd got any money left after - the - she had here - the insurance.
\par I:\tab Who was that came round then?
\par MC:\tab Well th
e people - the don't - they didn't call it - National Assistance like they get now, they used to call it Parish Relief. Well they come from Braintree or Dunmow just the same. To see - 'cos even then you didn't get it anyhow, no more than you do now. Just 
h
ad to give all - 'cos we - we - us what was going to school. I we had to have a card to say that we'd been to school, and give it up when we left, and then when we was fourteen we weren't allowed any more, we had to go out to work. 'Cos my sister next to 
m
e, she's fourteen, she had to go out the next week. See, because she wasn't going to school they didn't allow her anything, although it was only two shillings. I think she had - a little bread or something. But not in the way of money. So we had to take t
hese cards to school to say we'd been to school and when we'd left.
\par I:\tab An inspector came round though did he?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Would he come round quite often then?
\par MC:\tab Oh well - well you see the - I forget how long these cards lasted for. But - they'd got it do
wn in their books like they do anything else. They - they know when me sister was leaving school, and then she had to get a job, go out work. And then these two shillings were stopped.
\par I:\tab So it was too shillings for each child at school?
\par MC:\tab Yeah.
\par I:\tab And then something for your mother as well?
\par MC:\tab Yes. But even then that weren't much was it. I don't know whether she got a little bread or whether she didn't.
\par I:\tab You remember this man coming round though do you?
\par MC:\tab Well - I don't know who he was but I remember him - him coming round.
\par I:\tab Do you remember him coming round several times?
\par MC:\tab Yes, to me mother but you see I didn't know what - I couldn't say what it was all about at the time, but she's told me since. See, we've learned a lot more - since me father d
ied, she's told us, but we knew the people were there, but we didn't really sort of know what they was on about all the time. Yes.
\par I:\tab You didn't get free meals at school I suppose?
\par MC:\tab Well there's nothing of that down then. Nothing whatever. Oh no, you had to take - take it and just have a drop of water if you was - thirsty. Nothing else.
\par I:\tab What did you feel was the attitude of other people to the fact that you were on this poor relief?
\par MC:\tab Well no, I don't know if they - was - any - kinder to me mother or not, I know - just can't remember.
\par I:\tab You didn't remember children making remarks or anything?
\par MC:\tab No. No. But this woman what - what previously done the washing
, I think they allowed - allowed mother for the - her washing, in addition you see. 'Cos she couldn't pay her half a crown out of what she was getting 'cos mother still - 'cos they thought me mother was going out to work.
\par I:\tab They thought she was going out?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab But she wasn't?
\par MC:\tab No. Well he had never been to work. See she weren't strong enough to do the work.
\par I:\tab But they expected her to?
\par MC:\tab They expected her to do it because she was young you see. Before they'd grant her anything. I remember that.
\par I:\tab Did they make her sell any of the furniture or anything?
\par MC:\tab No. Oh no, no. Oh no, still kept the home going just the same. No. Then you see - in the - in a few years afterwards me elder brother he got in connected with another man and he was a bachelo
r, and his mother had died - and - and he brought him home a
\par I:\tab But at first you would have had an elder brother who was earning would you?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, yes, 'cos one of 'em was earning when dad - in fact I believe two of 'em was must have been.
\par I:\tab That must have helped a lot.
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes, two of 'em was, this one what I was just telling you about what - what went in the Army what - what was - wasn't quite the thing when he came out, and me older brother of all of us. One brother, he's - he's the eldest, we
ll we had a sister, the one - that one I told you what died, and then this brother came next. So he was working you see. And he weren't married of course.
\par I:\tab They stayed at home did they then?
\par MC:\tab Well he got - he did get married in the end but he weren't married then. They none of 'em were married when father died. No.
\par I:\tab So really the elder brother took your father's place?
\par MC:\tab Yes, something like that. And then the - other brother 'til I say he had to go in the - in the - Army. Well then there's two - two or three of the sisters out to work.
\par I:\tab Any of them living out then?
\par MC:\tab They used to go out you see, they used to call it in service, go out in big houses for other women, then they slept in. Was allowed out - about half a day a week or something like t
hat. That's how - that's how we went on. Didn't go in - none of 'em didn't go in factories or anything. Well then they eventually - married.
\par I:\tab So there weren't so many of you actually at home, how many were in fact living in home when your father died?
\par MC:\tab At home? Well - me oldest sister - and me, that was two, me brother three, sister four, five of us - that - that wasn't doing anything, yes.
\par I:\tab Five that weren't doing anything?
\par MC:\tab Yes, but then sister next to me - was - see I was ten - well then she'd got two or three years to go to school. I think you left at thirteen then though. Yes. I left when I was eleven. Yes.
\par I:\tab Why was that?
\par MC:\tab I was learning too quick. That's the truth.
\par I:\tab You passed the test then did you?
\par MC:\tab Well we didn'
t have no test. Never had not test, we never had - we never went in for exams at out school, but - no, they said that was a worrying me. The year before then I had to keep away for three months. And me sister was - two years and three months old - older t
han me and they talked about putting her up - me put - going up in her standard and she coming down in mine. No, they all said if - if - if mother had have had the money and we was in a different position, I'd have done well at school. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you like it at school then?
\par MC:\tab I used to like it. Yes. Oh yes, I was doing well at school. What we learnt then, but I ain't going to say we learnt the things they do now.
\par I:\tab What did they teachers say was important at that time?
\par MC:\tab Well they said long as you could read and write, I knew all me sums. That didn't seem a bit of trouble. No, they was not any trouble at all. I was eleven in the October and left at Christmas, and I ain't been since.
\par I:\tab When did you start then?
\par MC:\tab Five. Five.
\par I:\tab Was it boys and girls?
\par MC:\tab 
Yes, mixed, yes. You kept in one room 'til - oh I suppose about nine or ten, they - they called that the first class, and then you went in the - master's room in another room, in standards, that's how we went on at school. Starting from the first standa
rd. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were the teachers keen on manners?
\par MC:\tab Well they weren't too bad considering that was a - just a little - well there was a master and his wife and his daughter, they was all teachers. And my - the man was the head - well the master, you didn't 
call him a headmaster, you just called 'em schoolmaster, and the governess that was his wife. And the daughter was his teacher. Then we had another one from the little village post office. She used to teach. Yes, I used to like school.
\par I:\tab Were they strict, what happened if you did something they disapproved of?
\par MC:\tab Well they'd stand and face the corner. Stand there and face - or -you stand like this. There. Hands on - hands on head. Otherwise they weren't too bad.
\par I:\tab They didn't use the cane then?
\par MC:\tab They did. Oh yes. Boys used to have it. Yes.
\par I:\tab But not the girls?
\par MC:\tab Well, I never seen many girls get the cane. Teachers - when you small used the - pointer, take it out the easel. Blackboard and easel and they went with pointers to keep 'em in. She'd take that out sometimes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were they keen about children being tidy and clean?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, they did - didn't go too bad like the other places, no. No. 'Cos mother - was - they - sister always used to clean our shoes 'cos when we come home from school we used to have to stand 'em in this here passage. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you think the teachers treated all the children alike?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. Oh yes. We all sort of took - don't think she had any - many favourites. No. No, never had many favourites, not when I went to school.
\par I:\tab Were there any sort of groups or gangs in school, do you remember anything like that?
\par MC:\tab No they weren't too bad, they never got like they do these days, no, we'd have our little tiffs coming home perhaps, get a little bit of squabbling and - othe
rwise - no. No. I mean there's nothing for 'em to do, well some of the boys - if - in the summer you know they was haymaking or harvesting before they'd go home they'd go across the fields. But - we - we weren't supposed to do that coming home, we had, to
 go straight home first. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was it a church school?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Was only that one school, and that's pulled down now. Pity. That's where my sister lives right opposite, her - when they was - pulling it down, oh, she said, ain't it a pity, she said, pullin
g our school down, 'cos there was - I mean they could ha
\par I:\tab At the time did you want to go on with school?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. I did. I used to like it. Yes, I liked school.
\par I:\tab Was it because of the money you left you think?
\par MC:\tab No, they said 'cos I was learning - no, we didn't pay no money. It was just that I was learn - I was learning - it was worrying me - worrying me brain or something. I was learning too quick.
\par I:\tab Was it because they wanted you to start earning?
\par MC:\tab No, I did
n't go - no. I didn't go - I didn't really go out then 'til I was sixteen. I had one little - one job went of - Henham Windmill taking children out, but I never stopped but I never really come out really to earn money then 'til I was - sixteen, just on si
xteen. So I kept at home.
\par I:\tab This was a little job taking children out?
\par MC:\tab Taking children out. That's all.
\par I:\tab You did that for a while at school?
\par MC:\tab No, after I'd left school. After I left - when I was about twelve, thirteen.
\par I:\tab Who was that for then?
\par MC:\tab Some - some people what lived in the farmhouse - at Henham. I only stayed fortnight.
\par I:\tab You took them for a walk or something you mean?
\par MC:\tab Took 'em out during the day.
\par I:\tab Why did you leave so quickly then?
\par MC:\tab Well, I didn't like it. No, and I was only having eighteen pence a week. So I never went back.
\par I:\tab You got bored you mean?
\par MC:\tab Well that weren't though being at home I suppose. After being with all your brothers and sisters. Although the others had to go out just the same, we all had to make a start. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you spend the time at home, helping your mother?
\par MC:\tab Yes, yes, just roaming about helping mother and - and then I used to go up to school, and meet the others coming out. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par MC:\tab No, no. But as I say we didn't go out until father died, but - didn't make no difference afterwards, we sort of - kept in touch with the other children, she didn't seem to mind who we -
\par I:\tab Didn't mind who you played with?
\par MC:\tab No. Well we generally had the same ones that lived up the same road you see. Yes. 'Cos was quite a few of us. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you get any kind of special friends when you were a schoolchild?
\par MC:\tab Oh I did have one. But I - I don't know where - where she is now. We used to - play ho
pscotch, hoop and tops and - yes. Yes. They was all the plays that time of day, now you don't see a child with a top, that's all died out. Used to get a bit - we used to stop the men and say, have you got a bit of string? We wanted a bit of string to put 
o
n a stick to hit this top. Of course there was some special ones that you used - a good hit would go miles down the road. Oh yes. But really we did have some fun - out in the country going to school. It seemed to be the more attractive, in the country tha
n what there is here really. 'Cos you can do much just going to school just here and coming back, not on the main road can you. But we did at Broxted, I mean, we used to make our own fun and - have, some good times really.
\par I:\tab You didn't eat the hawthorn?
\par MC:\tab Berries. Yes, we used to pick them and blackberries. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were there any sports when you were a child?
\par MC:\tab Well only just - school sports when we broke up, we'd go in a few races you know in the - field near the school and - as I said they had these few swings come. Then they'd give us a tea.
\par I:\tab The girls didn't play cricket or football?
\par MC:\tab No. No, they never had games like - well, only when they played about with the school, not on their own like, they never had anything like that at school. No.
\par I:\tab You didn't play that on your own at all?
\par MC:\tab Well, we just played with the boys and girls.
\par I:\tab You did?
\par MC:\tab Yes. We didn't always have a cricket bat, but I made - they made one out of a bit of wood. Yes. Done that out of a bit of wood. Oh, played rounders.
 Yes. Played rounders. Yes. And skipping. We used to play skipping. But you don't see the children do that even these days, and we used to have a long skipping rope go right across the road and we - no end of us used to skip all together. But I don't see 
any of these children doing it. Oh yes, skipping and spinning tops come then hopps.
\par I:\tab Were there any horse races?
\par MC:\tab No. No. No, weren't no horse races, no, no. Oh nothing like that, no. We used to go round the meadows - picking blackberries and - nuts. N
uts, they'll soon be coming, nuts, hedge nuts. On the hedges you know. And hazelnuts, now they call 'em. Yes. Then - go round find chestnuts. And then we used to go around picking crab apples 'cos people used to like to make crab apple jelly. Or crab appl
e wine. But you couldn't eat them 'cos they was - too sour. Oh yes, we - we had our fun. Yes. As I say, there was the ditches and the ponds and - we'd go in the pond and in the ditches. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You say that there's got to be the rich and the poor?
\par MC:\tab Yes. And the rich can't do without the poor.
\par I:\tab Were you brought up to think that?
\par MC:\tab Well we was told that because the rich can't - because - they - they always put - look down on a farm - on men what work on farms, and yet they can't do without them, be
cause if they didn't work an the farm and get the corn in, well wouldn't have any would we? No, well the rich can't do without the poor. No, the rich are glad of the poor to go to work for 'em aren't they? Yeah, we was told all that when we went to school
.
\par I:\tab When you went to school?
\par MC:\tab Yes. And said no one should never despise another one, however - if they were rich or whether they're poor. They should always speak to one another. Well so you should really. Yes. And my mother used to say - if you haven't
 - that don't hurt anybody to speak, you don't have to pay to speak, she said, the least you could do is to - answer anybody. See? And we've always been brought up to that. She said, never mind, if they don't like to speak to you, you can just speak. Whic
h we do.
\par I:\tab If you met a rich person when you were a child were you expected to curtsey or anything?
\par MC:\tab Well no, that's - we really - really the rich - real lady will speak to you. They do. They speak to you more than - as my mother used to say, anyone - t
hat's got up and think they're a lady those are the ones what won't speak to you, they think they're above you. And they - perhaps they haven't got anything really. And to be clean, mother always used to say, that don't - that don't cost you much to be cl
ean, water's cheap enough. So - well it was in the country, 'cos we got - got ours free didn't we.
\par I:\tab Can you think of somebody who was called a real lady at that time?
\par MC:\tab No, only - only Lady Warrick. We never had any other ladies living there, and she wo
uld speak to you, well she - well she - she used to come and talk - visit me mother, and she would speak to you. She never passed you one - passed you one side. And if you went up after dripping she'd always ask you how you was getting on. Yes. And she wa
s a Lady. But - as mother said, when - some of those have been - think - they've got on a bit and got up, and then they won't speak to you, they think they've got more than you have. Probably they have but - you can still speak just the same can't you?

\par I:\tab Were there some people than in the village who'd sort of risen?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yeah, that had and that thought well I - I ain't going to speak to her, I ain't going - I - I'm not going to speak to him, no. My mother said well if they don't speak just pass them by
. Let them know that you're as good as what they are. What's my mother used to say. Talking to us. But my mother - well she's not - she was my mother but - I thought I've heard her - see she was far too - oh she could speak ever so nice. She could speak a
s
 if she was speaking to a lady. And she'd - and - as she said she'd been about and she'd had all this here - but it didn't make any difference to her. She could be one of us and she could be in - in a - in a better position if she liked. I can show you a 
photo when you come here. Well in fact I think I've got it - there now, I'll get it.
\par I:\tab Did you often go fruit picking then?
\par MC:\tab Yeah, well they had a fruit picking at Halesdon, where they picked raspberries, strawberries, gooseberries, blackcurrants - and 
I went. Have someone come round then and we was in the middle of the field. So we had to come just as we was. That was mine.
\par I:\tab You went quite often in the summer to do that?
\par MC:\tab In the summer. While it lasted. Generally about a month. Yes.
\par I:\tab Just the sisters, not your mother?
\par MC:\tab No, mother never went. No, if we was home we went you see, I went. And my - first year I went, that weren't the year, when my mother said, wall if you do fairly well, she said, I'll buy you a new frock. And a hat. And 
a pair of shoes. A pair of boots they ware. Yes. Yes, she was dear old girl, mother was. Of course she was bedridden - one or two of the farmers. Not really anybody else really. No.
\par I:\tab What about a doctor?
\par MC:\tab We didn't live in the village, he lived at Thaxted. Yes, we didn't have any doctors live in the village.
\par I:\tab So it was just the farmers?
\par MC:\tab Yes, who was more or less the richer people you see, that's about all. No.
\par I:\tab Really Lady Warrick was the nearest big house was she?
\par MC:\tab Next one and she lived at Eastham. They lived at Little Eastham, well that's a long way really.
\par I:\tab There was Boreham Hall wasn't there?
\par MC:\tab Well that was on the way to Thaxted, yes, but that was near us, it was between Boxted and Thaxted.
\par I:\tab You didn't see much of them?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. No, it was - no, not that, no. I daresay she done a few things in the village but I mean she didn't really live in our village. There weren't - what I call any - so called people in our village, only the farmers.
\par I:\tab What about the vicar?
\par MC:\tab Well he - wel
l they never - never classed vicars as well off did they. No. No. And he's a very old gentleman, I know - the one - what was there when I was a child but - I was the last one he married before I - he was over seventy a good bit. Yes. But that - I mean tha
t was about all, because there's only one little tiny shop, a general stores, well I suppose the woman - and her husband went to work so - well weren't all that roses was they.
\par I:\tab Did you have to call the farmers sir?
\par MC:\tab No. My sons - my son - my sons, my 
brothers worked for one farmer and me father worked for another. The old farmer where me brothers were they were a lot like us. Laugh and talk and swear. Mother used to say, oh - there comes old Mr Lanes. Oh no, we never called him sir, nothing. No, he wa
s
 just like one of us. Just a - that's a - no, the only ones what you could say was a little better off. Then - then never heard of anyone having their own house, I don't believe even the farms really belonged to them in a sense sort of thing, they sort of
 hired 'em and - worked in - in the farm, managers and that like. 'Course that's improved a bit now. That's since I've got - these last few years, 'cos there's been council houses and everything else put up. Yes.
\par I:\tab There wasn't a policeman in the village?
\par MC:\tab Well there was for a little time, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you see anything of him then?
\par MC:\tab Yeah, we always used to see him, his son lives up here now. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he chase the children if they were going after apples and things?
\par MC:\tab Well - perhaps he did you know, but he weren't too bad, no, no. No.
\par I:\tab You don't remember - I've often been told of the policemen sort of giving them a flick with his cape and things like that.
\par MC:\tab Well he'd run after 'em sometimes you know. And there used to be one or two really very 
very old men that - who always used to get drinking. And they - sort of start making a noise - then, and he'd go after them then, but otherwise they weren't really too bad you know. Then in - after he died we never had any. I don't think they've got one n
ow, there now, not in the village. No. And schoolmaster, he was only like an ordinary man. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were there any families which were thought of as rough?
\par MC:\tab Well there ware one or two. In the - years gone when I was a little girl, but they've sort of died off now.
\par I:\tab What was different about them, was it drink?
\par MC:\tab Drink then you see, yes, if they got a little money they would go and drink. Then they'd have a squabble between theirselves. Yes. Else otherwise - weren't too bad, 'cos to mean you couldn
't go nowhere at nights, that only got, you could just go down to this little old pub if they wanted to go out. No. That was when I was quite small that was. Yes.
\par I:\tab If somebody did something that the people disapproved of do you remember any kind of rough music or something like that to show how they felt?
\par MC:\tab Well no, perhaps they'd have - be - be a few loggerheads together and - that - but not really - they all seemed to, be sort of to be more or less together like, there'd only just be these odd few as 
I tell you what would - did go to the pub, otherwise the
\par I:\tab I was thinking when I was reading your essay, you remember the story you told about the night your sister was born?
\par MC:\tab My sister's daughter?
\par I:\tab No, the one when you were very small.
\par MC:\tab Oh. Oh yep. Me brother was next and then my sister.
\par I:\tab When you were four?
\par MC:\tab That's right. I was four in the October and - four in the October and - this is October, and I'll be seventy next Thursday.
\par I:\tab Why did you go into the washtub?
\par MC:\tab Well you see, mother w
as short of beds. 'Cos I mean I - I - I was the ninth child, and then me brother he made ten and then me sister was eleven, the eleventh one, it was only for - say for a couple or three nights 'cos old people that time of day didn't
\par I:\tab Your father never did any part time jobs as well as his ordinary one?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, 'cos his cowman job lasted him all day, that's the reason we was put to bed before he come home, 'cos he didn't get home I suppose 'til six o'clock time, they didn't those days on the farm. We us
ed to have - bed by half past five. Six o'clock we was late. Quarter to six and that we was late see. No, my father never done any odd jobs. Only - well it was his own - gardening and allotment, that was as much as he could do, see, plenty of work that wa
s
. Yes. I mean in those days people used to go cutting hedges and - they used to get all the wood and call it faggots you know. Cut 'em up in bundles, well that, we used to - that used to be the morning's wood tied up in - and me father used to have to cho
p that up ready for mother to light the fire with the next day.
\par I:\tab He'd get it from the hedges by the roads?
\par MC:\tab Yes. You see, all the men on the farms in that time of day used to cut hedges down after the harvest and that was - and then they had the firewo
od, well they - well as long like that - well you've seen beansticks and pea sticks haven't you, well thy was tied up and they called them faggots, and then got a thin piece and tied it round. See, and then - they used to bring all these faggots home when
 they'd finished - in the - farm carts, well that was used for - that. was - all what he did, really did. See?
\par I:\tab And you can remember the harvest, you used to go to the harvest yourself did you?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, in the fields when we got a little - older, for m
e brother's, take their dinners - down the fields. That was - that was nice that was 'cos I mean - as you know, mother used to - at - that time of day used to make meat puddings, 'cos you never heard much about roast beef that time of day. Meat puddings w
as a farm - labourers dinner. And used to make little ones, what they call meat dumplings. About as big as that for one person. And I used to like that - so they used to say, do you want a bit girl?
\par I:\tab You'd take them down for your brothers then?
\par MC:\tab In - i
n a dinner hour you see, for their dinners, if they was near. But - which - well sometimes that was a good walk for us really. If - that was when we were home from school because in that time of day we only had five week, or just turned the month. Not eig
ht weeks like they do now. No. 'Course there's other children as well, that was the only time we was allowed out really. 'Til me father died.
\par I:\tab So you'd have quite a lot of fun in the harvest fields?
\par MC:\tab Yes. That was - that be - then you see that time of 
day they used to go gleaning. Gleaning the wheat for the chickens, my goodness there's not - not anything of that done at all these days is it. Was nothing to - to - glean not now, not with these combines whatever they're called. No.
\par I:\tab I wasn't quite sure, I asked you about whether your father took in any interest in politics and I think you said no?
\par MC:\tab No, well I - well I - as a matter of fact I - I - I don't know as we heard a lot about 'em in that - you know, in the little village, they might have got 
a few of the - what I call the better class people, but we - we didn't - I never heard many that time of day. Not -
\par I:\tab You don't know at all what his views were then?
\par MC:\tab Well of course he'd be all Labour as you call it, being a farm - a - a farm, 'cos they were weren't they.
\par I:\tab Would have been Liberal then?
\par MC:\tab Yes. I know - I used to hear him talk about Conservatives but -
\par I:\tab He didn't like them you mean?
\par MC:\tab Well apparently not, not being on a farm would they, 'cos they - see. No.
\par I:\tab But he never went to political meetings?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. Well I - I - I - I only remember one voting when I was a little girl, I know - I - I remember that now, we used to say vote, vote, vote for
 Colonel Maxted. But who the other one was I can't remember. But whether he went or not you see because you see he'd be - I know they kept open 'til eight well then he had quite a way to walk from one end of the village to the other in the village but whe
ther he went or not I wouldn't know 'cos I'd be in bed. See?
\par I:\tab Who was shouting vote, vote, vote then?
\par MC:\tab The children. Schoolchildren. Then we used to wear ribbons didn't we.
\par I:\tab What colour ribbon did you wear then?
\par MC:\tab We never had any. We never had any
. We didn't have any, but I know the children did wear - just the same as they did for the - boat race didn't they. Used to wear ribbons years ago, dark blue and light blue but you don't hear nothing about that now.
\par I:\tab You used to for the boat race?
\par MC:\tab Well, if we could get a little piece but I mean - mother never bought us any but - well whether we understood what it was for I - I don't know. No.
\par I:\tab When you were young did you feel one of your brothers or sisters was your special companion?
\par MC:\tab One of the
 eldest sisters, because - because she had to keep at home, sort of look after younger ones. Well not - she wasn't really the eldest, not the eldest of all she was third sister down. But - I know mother kept her at home until me father died to help her be
cause she couldn't cope with us. She couldn't cope with us all I suppose. Yes.
\par I:\tab So you were especially friendly with her?
\par MC:\tab We were friendly because she had us - do more for us like, the others as they got - 'cos they used to leave school at fourteen th
en, or thirteen and a half, and go out go out to - well they call it service. Go in another - lady's house and help with their work, you see and live in. Which is very hard work I can tell you in that time of day. Yes. Well I started work for - I only had
 eighteen pence a week. That's all.
\par I:\tab When was that then?
\par MC:\tab When I worked - I went - I was about fourteen. I didn't go far, I just - and in the little next village, Henham, where - where it is and - take the children out but I only stayed a fortnight. Ye
s. But I mean really to go out to work you only went - girls that time of day was really hard worked because you had to get up here - about quarter to six to call the master be - for him to catch the train.
\par I:\tab But later on you did go to live in yourself didn't you?
\par MC:\tab Later on, when I was sixteen, went with me - another elder sister 'cos I - her husband was in the First World War. Kept her company. But I was sixteen then.
\par I:\tab Where did you go to?
\par MC:\tab Bishops Stortford. Yes. And -
\par I:\tab But you lived with your sister?
\par MC:\tab I was daygirl, worked daily and then went home at night. To be company with my sister.
\par I:\tab What sort of hours did you have to work there?
\par MC:\tab From seven o'clock in the morning 'til -just - sort of after teatime, six o'clock time.
\par I:\tab Would you get a half-day?
\par MC:\tab Well not when I was daygirl. Oh perhaps we had a hour or two off, you know, wasn't all that busy, but you couldn't claim half a day not being a day girl. No.
\par I:\tab Did you have to work Sundays as well?
\par MC:\tab Yes, yes. Generally come home in the afternoon on Sundays. Yes.
\par I:\tab Would there be a paid holiday during the year or not?
\par MC:\tab Well not for daygirls, no, no daygirls.
\par I:\tab What exactly did you have to do in that job then?
\par MC:\tab Keep - do the bedrooms, wash up, do all - you know, everything for them like. Perhaps you had a hour off in the afternoon. 'Til teatime.
\par I:\tab Were there other people helping in the house?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. Not where I was. No. That was a - headmaster's place at Bishops Stortford College. Yes. There was - two boys went to
 school, only the school was only just down the road. And he used to come home midday you see to lunch when the schoolchildren was having their dinners as well. But the boys - we - of course they came home as well, yes. But the girl, she was away.
\par I:\tab This was the headmaster?
\par MC:\tab Yes, headmaster - one of the headmaster's of Bishops Stortford College, 'course - well not there is it now, they're all gone now.
\par I:\tab You didn't have to cook though?
\par MC:\tab Well I helped. Helped but she did the miss - - the mistress did the main cooking. But - of course there's all the preparing the vegetables and everything - and that.
\par I:\tab How did she treat you then?
\par MC:\tab Oh very - very nice person she was, yes, very nice person. Yes.
\par I:\tab Sort of took an interest in you as a person?
\par MC:\tab Ye
s. You do what they tell you mind you, they took an interest in you. But if you never - well. But I - I can tell you some places where the girls weren't so - were - different places they had rough times with some of these people, they put upon them. Yes. 
But girls -
\par I:\tab Some of your sisters you mean?
\par MC:\tab Well one sister, but I mean in the village, 'cos all the village sort of girls went out to do this sort of work, there's nothing else for 'em to do in - no factories or anything then in - well, weren't none 
then, none now in Broxted. No. But - anyway that was how lived - that's what we had to do for a living. But -
\par I:\tab Did she expect to - did she mind what you did when you were out of the house? If people were living in I think the mistress was rather concerned about how they behaved when they went out. Would you say that was true?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, they - 'cos you had to get in at a certain time. Yes.
\par I:\tab But you didn't have to though did you?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, 'cos I was - once I'd came away I was finished 'til the next morning.
\par I:\tab But she didn't interfere with your home life?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. Oh no. Not at all. No.
\par I:\tab Did she like to know who your friends were and things like that?
\par MC:\tab No. She didn't - she - this one never seemed to bother you see. She knew I went home to me sister's. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you keep all the money yourself then?
\par MC:\tab What little we had.
\par I:\tab You didn't pay your sister?
\par MC:\tab Oh I had to give her a little for me keep, 'co
s you see - wives didn't get a lot that time of day as they do now if they're in the forces do they. No. Oh didn't get much that time of day. And then we was rationed. Rationed then as was - as well as we was in the last world war. Yes. Oh no, didn't get 
much then the money. Well all the money I had went - left her - left to get married was two pound a month. Well -
\par I:\tab Where were you getting that, was that somewhere else?
\par MC:\tab That's somewhere else in Bishops Stortford.
\par I:\tab How long were you with the headmaster then?
\par MC:\tab Oh - about -two years I su - about two years or something like that, 'til me sister husband came home. Yes.
\par I:\tab If you were tired during the day was there somewhere where you could sit down?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Yes. You had a - a room to sit in. Yes. Oh you -
\par I:\tab Your own room?
\par MC:\tab Yes, you and you could take - your own needlework or knitting and do anything like that. In about an hour or so in the afternoon 'til they came home to tea. Oh yes. Yes, that wasn't bad at all but -
\par I:\tab Did you have much to do with the boys?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. No, no, nothing to do with them.
\par I:\tab She looked after the children?
\par MC:\tab She looked after - yes. Only had to make the beds and do the rooms. That was our work. Yes, that was our work.
\par I:\tab Did you sit and eat your dinner with them?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, you had - all maids do, they call them maids, they all had their din - meals on their own, they didn't - didn't live with the - mistress as they called her. No, you didn't - dine with them.
\par I:\tab For dinner she sent you off to your own little room you mean?
\par MC:\tab In the kitchenette - in the kitchen. Like they called that the kitchen then there's a kitchenette, well you had your in the kitchen. See now - when you took the dinners in - they cut yours off, and rung a bell and you fetched it. That's what we
 had to go on.
\par I:\tab What sort of food did they have, was it good food?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, good food. Oh one place - I was living in Stansted then, - that's where the airport is now, part of it down there, was a farmhouse. Oh well we lived extremely well, if we were
n't having pheasants we was having rabbits and that, on the farm. Yes, that it was good there. Yes.
\par I:\tab That was later on was it?
\par MC:\tab That
 was after that, yes. Yes, that was after that. So I mean you got some of these girls what went out as - what they called service, perhaps some of 'em didn't stay about a month. Then they'd have to look out for another job. And the trouble was if you went
 from one place to another you had - had to get a reference. Yes. But you see if you'd come from say this place and the girls kept leaving, well they knew that weren't the girls, it was the mistress.
\par I:\tab So people would know then?
\par MC:\tab Yes, would know you see, cos if none of the girls stopped, the - all - all the girls couldn't be the same could they.
\par I:\tab How would you find out about that though?
\par MC:\tab Well, you - you see, you got in contact with different people and they - if you heard that that one had had all them maids in that little while they would say, well that one can't be much - much of a place, cos the girls don't stop.
\par I:\tab They'd know in the village?
\par MC:\tab Yes, they'd know you see, you get from one to - one tells the other. But as for - that was as far as I went, Bishop Stortford.
\par I:\tab So you had two years with the headmaster and then you went to another place in Bishop Stortford?
\par MC:\tab Where did I go. Oh - oh yes, where a woman - she'd got three little boys. She kept a milliners shop in Stortford. Yes. That w
as - what you call a hat shop that - that was a miliners shop. And then this sister what I lived with - with during the war, she used to come in daily.
\par I:\tab To the same place?
\par MC:\tab Same place. And before then my eldest sister of all was - used to be a maid there. Before then. But I forget how long -
\par I:\tab What was it like there?
\par MC:\tab Well that was very nice but I took children out and somehow or other I didn't - I developed measles. Which was a funny thing, she sent me home. Which she shouldn't have done because I
 - I travelled home by myself from Stortford to - Hayldon in the train. Well when I got home I gave it to me brothers. And - and consequently they had it worse than I did, but so - she wouldn't have me back no more because she had to get someone else whil
e I was home, but - they made you stay away then about a month at a time. But they don't now do they?
\par I:\tab Did you like it less living in?
\par MC:\tab Well, no, I wasn't very keen on living in.
\par I:\tab Why not?
\par MC:\tab No. Well I mean you was so many hours on your own weren't you?
\par I:\tab It was a bit lonely?
\par MC:\tab Well it - it is, yes, but I mean my sisters and they used to do it, they done it more than I did, I - not then being on me own. So many hours on your own, all your evening.
\par I:\tab Did you feel you had less freedom when you were living in?
\par MC:\tab Well you only got half a day out - say on Wednesday or Thursdays, that was mostly Thursday, and every other Sunday. Well the other Sundays you had to stay in. Well I mean - that really - really weren't much was it? Not for a young person t
o be tied to one place all the time.
\par I:\tab And nobody really to talk to?
\par MC:\tab No. See - same girls went where they kept three or four maids, that weren't so bad then. But - most of us, we went where was only kept one, then they called you a - a general, 'cos y
ou had everything. You learnt everything from cooking to washing and everything, but if they went where there's two or three, perhaps one would be what they called lady's maid. Well she didn't have nothing to do with the kitchen. Nothing at all. Noth - no
thing to do with cooking or anything. And the housemaids were - well they only made beds and did bedrooms.
\par I:\tab You never want to a place like that?
\par MC:\tab No. No, I never went to a place, only when - they call us jack of all trades. Mind you, in the country they said us made best wives. Because you did know how to cook when you got married, now half of 'em don't - and that's true en't it?
\par I:\tab They taught you to cook?
\par MC:\tab 
Oh yes, you learnt plain cooking but if you could do plain cooking - because you knew you would have a - a - more or less a husband in the same circumstances as yourself, if you could do plain cooking they said that was everything. The other came to you a
fterwards. Yes. Which we could. 'Cos some, of the girls nowadays can't even cook a - a egg I did hear.
\par I:\tab You wouldn't have learnt cooking as a daygirl though?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Oh yes, 'cos you had cooked lunch. Yes. Oh yes, you started.
\par I:\tab When you were at home as a girl you were taught a bit?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, well we used to watch our mother. Yes. We sort of knew, yes. We weren't children that were sent out and didn't know nothing. No. No.
\par I:\tab Did she teach you things like laying tables?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Lay tables, different to what we do at home.
\par I:\tab Just more things on the table?
\par MC:\tab On the table, 'cos we didn't have side plates. Well we - never had enough room to get one plate let alone two or three. But we knew how it could be done. Oh my mother did. Oh my mother knew how
 things should be done, but you couldn't follow that up. No, no.
\par I:\tab Before you went as a daygirl did your mother sort of tell you the sort of thing that would be expected of you?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. And we - we knew - within a little. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you remember the mistress being particularly strict about anything?
\par MC:\tab Well - she - most - I don't know really - certain things, I mean you had to do certain things in a certain way and all that but - no well -
\par I:\tab What sort of things do you mean?
\par MC:\tab Making be
ds was - was - which they do a little different some of 'em to we do when we're home. Yes. 'Course I mean - well, some of 'em had got bathrooms which we hadn't had - had - had at all, not bathrooms. But you soon got used to it. And if you'd been brought u
p to work things sort of naturally came to you really. Yes.
\par I:\tab When you were a daygirl did you have to answer the door or anything?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they have cards then?
\par MC:\tab Well - yes, yes if the - if the mistress - was out when anyone - whoever co
me to the door would say, well will you give her this when you come in, that was a card to say where they'd come from. Yes. Or if you thought that was someone local you just said, well, whoever it was - so and so had called and they'd be back again. See? 
'
Cos sometimes same one'd - call regularly you know, and the mistress was out and say well we'll come back at such a time. 'Cos she - went out and done her shopping, well she used to - go on a bicycle. Down the village, 'cos we lived on - on the - Hagam Ro
a
d. I don't know if you know where that is. Yes. Well - the - well you must have seen - as you go up the Hagham Road - road on the left is called Maize Green Road and they're building new - schools and all that up there now. Well that's where I lived, ther
e. Up Maize - up Maize Green Road. Yes.
\par I:\tab Further up the road?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Not in the main school building?
\par MC:\tab Well - the college was up Maize Green Road. But that's Boys College. Yes. On the left - that's right, on the left hand side as you went up. It's just it's only just - out of the town, just straight -
\par I:\tab It was the boy's college headmaster that you were with?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. And he lived further up. Duchane his name was. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they have dinner parties in the evening?
\par MC:\tab Well if they did I didn't go back. No. No. I didn't go. Well I presumed they did because there'd be some washing up left overnight to do in the morning, but if there was much - but I never went back not in the evening.
\par I:\tab So she would look after that herself?
\par MC:\tab Yes, she'd do that herself you see. Oh if - if she was going to have anybody she'd say would you mind doing a few extra vegetables or something like that. But I never went back to help. No. Never went back to help.
\par I:\tab What sort of people used to come and visit her?
\par MC:\tab Well the master - the other - master's wives, the younger master's wives and her own - own people of course.
\par I:\tab Her own relations?
\par MC:\tab Yes. All those. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she have sort of meetings in her house?
\par MC:\tab No, not in the house, no. Oh - oh I - not real meetings, there'd be some would come and have sort of - she called it at home day. At home day.
\par I:\tab What happened then?
\par MC:\tab Well they sat round and had a cup of tea, that'd be in the afternoon, but not men. Their wives.
\par I:\tab And you'd have to come in and serve tea?
\par MC:\tab Well, just a cup of tea. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she make you dress up in uniform?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, 'cos you - you had - on - what they called print dresses in the morning, then you had to wear black in the afternoon. But then it got to navy b
lue. And - a - a little bit more fancier apron in the afternoon. You didn't change in what I call dresses, you had to keep to your uniform because - have it - all that's died out now hasn't it. Everything's died out. They knew you was the maid right enoug
h, with - a cap on your head.
\par I:\tab And you had to call her madam did you?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What would she call you?
\par MC:\tab Well call you by your Christian name. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have anything much to do with Mr Duchane or wouldn't he really sort of talk to you?
\par MC:\tab 
Oh - oh yes, he'd talk, but not a lot because he used to have to - if he wasn't - up, I used to have to boil a kettle, get his hot - shaving water in the mornings. Yes. 'Cos I got there at seven. But he - he wasn't up because he hadn't got far to go to 
school, not to get there at nine, just down the road. And then there'd be the boy's breakfast.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me how the day went, you'd start by boiling water?
\par MC:\tab Well start getting in the - help getting the breakfast, setting the breakfast. By the time
 they'd had their breakfast there'd be the wash - wash up and then - have to start work. Do bedrooms. Then be the hall and the dining room and - the other rooms. Oh there was plenty to do.
\par I:\tab So you'd spend the mornings cleaning out the rooms?
\par MC:\tab Cleaning out, doing the vegetables, help getting the dinner and then in the afternoon there'd be to wash up and then - sometimes there'd be all the extra silver to clean and - that's how we went on you see.
\par I:\tab Did she do it alongside you?
\par MC:\tab 
Oh no. Oh no, you - unless there was anything extra on, and then she'd say I'll give you a hand, but she just left you to it, of course she showed us when we went - when I went in first. Well what I'd got to do and what routine - routine I'd got to be. Mo
ndays was this and Tuesdays was that. I mean, they had a day for everything. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me the different days then?
\par MC:\tab Well Mondays and Tuesdays they'd be bed - doing the bedrooms and little bit and then Wednesday - it'd be the downstairs rooms, 
and - and Thursdays, and a Friday would be turn out - the kitchen, and the kitchenette. See to all them type of thing. Well that - that is how the day went. 'Cos - I mean nowadays you've got Hoovers and that haven't you, well we never. We had brooms and s
crubbing brushes. Scrub table. Well there's all that extra to do, and I mean they don't even now scrub the tables do they. Used to have a - like - Formica on the top of something.
\par I:\tab A lot of polishing to do was there?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they have a lot of ornaments in the house?
\par MC:\tab Well they did that time of day. One place I laughed because - you know you have pairs don't you? A pair of ornaments, this and that, and one - one woman - she wouldn't have 'em in pairs, she had 'em standing where - anyhow. On
e - a big one there and - and a small one here like that. And picture frames, she wouldn't have picture frames 'cos she said they weren't pictures. Well they're not really are they? No, well you wouldn't call them pictures. She had - views and all that so
rt of thing. Those were pictures. More - more or less all the same, some coloured and some black. She did have one or two little photos but she said they weren't pictures.
\par I:\tab Where was that then, where was she?
\par MC:\tab That was the same one at Stortford. Yes. Yes. And then I went to another one and she was, just the same. 'Cos - one I went to - one sister-in-law and one sister-in-law to the other one. See?
\par I:\tab How did you get the job first of all in Bishop Stortford?
\par MC:\tab Through me sister. Through my sister. Yes.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me a little about living with your sister like that, did you have children by then?
\par MC:\tab Yes, well - only - one girl. No. Yes, she had got a daughter, her eldest daughter, yes. And she went to school. Yes, well the eldest one, of course s
he was 'cos she was born the first day of the First World War. Yes. Her eldest daughter. I might forget 'cos there's so many in the family, oh dear I can't - I can't think of 'em all. Of course she was born, yes.
\par I:\tab The life there would be very much like at home would I?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes just about the same.
\par I:\tab The sort of cooking and so on?
\par MC:\tab Yes, just about the same as it was at home. Me sister and the - girl. That was up at Stortford. Windyhill, I don't know if you know where that is, where convent is. That 
- that Covent, it's right opposite the convent, those little cottages are pulled down now, that was on the - going round the road to Thorley. Yes, right in the corner. So I just had to go down Bowes Hill and just turn the corner, Pagham Road, and up Maize
 Green Road. And did I tell you when I went into the lamp post.
\par I:\tab You said that in your essay.
\par MC:\tab Yes, ran into the lamp post.
\par I:\tab Would you say that by that time there was more tinned food being used?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. No.
\par I:\tab Not even then?
\par MC:\tab Oh no.
\par I:\tab Not in the headmaster's house?
\par MC:\tab No. Weren't no tinned stuff much about then. Only - only - what they called -they used to call it bully beef didn't they, corned beef. Yes. But that more or less was you bought - bought - well enough didn't you. No.
\par I:\tab Did either of them use a gas cooker?
\par MC:\tab What - where I worked?
\par I:\tab Your sister or the headmistress?
\par MC:\tab No, a kitchen range. Yes, kitchen range. My sister don't - she hadn't got what they call a range you see, just a little old - cottage fireplaces with a little oven at the side but you - they weren't kitchen ranges. No.
\par I:\tab She'd got a sort of two-roomed cottage?
\par MC:\tab Yes. That's all. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of things were there to do in the evenings in Bishop Stortford?
\par MC:\tab Well there was - pictures. But I never went. No. I was eighteen when I went to pictures first. No, we just sat in - in. And - she'd do needlework, and we hadn't got - television, not wireless.
\par I:\tab Your sister never went out at all?
\par MC:\tab No. We just stayed in. Yes.
\par I:\tab You carried on going to church while you were there or did you give it up?
\par MC:\tab I went occasionally but I didn't go so much then as - well my sister was church as well. Yes. Well we was all church so - you know.
\par I:\tab What about the Girls Friendly Society, did you give that up?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Well they - that was given up. At home. Yes. Oh I never did go - not once I left home, not - Girls friendly Society. No.
\par I:\tab You didn't join any other sort of clubs there?
\par MC:\tab No. No, never joined any - at all. No.
\par I:\tab What about taking an interest in politics then, yourself?
\par MC:\tab No. No. No, never - never did.
\par I:\tab Not even votes for women?
\par MC:\tab No, I don't remember taking much interest in that - no, no. No. No, I don't. Well there weren't quite so much voting really was there, I never heard of much voting - when we was young as these - as these last few years. No. No.
\par I:\tab Did you make any new friends in Bishop Stortford?
\par MC:\tab Well migh
t have picked up with - I didn't actually keep 'em us friends, I might have - but that - that wasn't while I was with my sister. That was when I got older and I went - when I took this little boys out, we used to go in the Castle gardens, and then we - me
et another girl with some more children out like and when we went in. But then I didn't keep 'em up as friends. No.
\par I:\tab You'd just have a chat in the park?
\par MC:\tab Yes, that - must - that was all. Yes. No. I haven't really got outside of friends, not from - I was a girl, only the - ones I went to school with. And most of them have drifted apart, so - yes.
\par I:\tab I think you said it was about 1919 that you met your husband wasn't it?
\par MC:\tab Was it 1919?
\par I:\tab I think you said in the essay you'd known him for about four years when you got married, so was that when you were in Bishop Stortford that you met him?
\par MC:\tab No, that's when I was at the farm what I was telling you about, near his - near his home. Was it not -
\par I:\tab At Stansted?
\par MC:\tab Yes. 'Cos - he - he lived in the cottage with his dad and his dad worked on the farm where I was living. Well that was when he come out of - First World War. Was it 1919?
\par I:\tab About then it would be wouldn't it?
\par MC:\tab Well - suppose it would have been. I was eighteen. And I was eight - yes, it would be 1919 wouldn't it. I have to keep going back to those dates here. That's right, 'cos I was married when I was twenty-two.
\par I:\tab Was he working on the farm himself?
\par MC:\tab No, not him he wasn't. He wasn't doing anything much at the
 time. It's a really - these people he worked for lived down a - drive. Well the - the bakers wouldn't go down there, so they used to leave the bread at his mother's. And that's how I saw - I - I picked up with him. Yes. And me and another girl, we used t
o
 go church - 'cos she made us go to church Sunday evenings, well there was another girl, and she was - my husband's cousin, we used to pick her up the top of the road - and - there'd be two or three of, these lads and - we didn't know which one was which,
 
we kept - they kept whistling. Same as - my - the one I - you know, married after all. Yes, 'cos I used to go - his house - well I'd been there before he come home out the forces to pick this bread up and take - milk and that up. When he came - home out t
he forces. See?
\par I:\tab When you were living in were you allowed to go down and sort of visit him?
\par MC:\tab No. No. I - I used to see him as I used to go to church. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you actually get engaged then?
\par MC:\tab No. I'd been with him about four years before we were engaged. Three to four years. 'Cos I - I - I left that place afterwards, see, then I went to Bishop Stortford.
\par I:\tab You went back to Bishop Stortford?
\par MC:\tab Went back to Bishop Stortford. Yes. I - I was at the Herts and Essex High School then. That's where I - and that's where I left and got married.
\par I:\tab You were with one of the mistresses there you mean?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Lived in like do work there then. She'd got three or four children. But she - she was very good she was, 'cos - she'd allow him to come over - three times a week. And - in the evening.
\par I:\tab That was because you were engaged, they sort of thought it a bit difference once you were engaged?
\par MC:\tab Yes. And when we was married, we - after we'd been married a few months they went on holiday, we had to go over there and keep house - to keep the house for them. Yes. Yes, she was a very nice person, yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother help you set up house when you got married?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. No, she hadn't got nothing to - nothing to help - us on, but I mean she was a widow, been a widow all them years, you know.
\par I:\tab Did you save up at all then?
\par MC:\tab That - I didn't save up much because didn't get paid much. Two pound a month.
\par I:\tab But you did save up a bit?
\par MC:\tab I - I - I know and I didn't save a lot did I, but - my husband, he - I mean he'd got money, he'd just come out the forces and what he had that was through him really.
\par I:\tab That's how you bought the furniture and so on?
\par MC:\tab Yes, he got - well he had a little cottage then at Broxted. One room and a little tiny kitchenette and one bedroom so we didn't want much furniture. That's how gradually - then I went to work afterwards see. I -
\par I:\tab What did you do then?
\par MC:\tab Well I was at Broxted in that little cottage - I didn't - I used to go potatoing and fruit picking, I didn't go housework not then. Well then he got this job at Stansted - and - I - and then I -
\par I:\tab What was he doing there, on the nursery was that?
\par MC:\tab Yes, well then he left the nursery and then he - he got this job as a 
gardener up what we call the Stansted House, Stansted Hall, and then this cottage was - down behind in the woods. And then we - I - we went to there. Then I used to work in the big house then. 'Til I -
\par I:\tab As a maid again you mean?
\par MC:\tab Well, no, daily. They didn't call you maids then, they called you chars. After you was married. 'Til I had my son, well that was three years after I was married.
\par I:\tab You mean you did the same thing as if you were a daygirl?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab But they called you a char if you were married?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes, charring when you're married and -
\par I:\tab They called you Mrs did they?
\par MC:\tab Yes. But I done anything then. Helped - 'cos they - that - that place kept nine maids. So first I was helping one and then the other.
\par I:\tab Was it more fun when there were a lot of you?
\par MC:\tab Yes. I was helping the butler, helping the cook. Helping the laundry, all sorts of jobs I did then.
\par I:\tab You think - they had a better time really though?
\par MC:\tab Yes, Then -
\par I:\tab Would they have a kind of Christmas party and things like that?
\par MC:\tab 
Yes, well didn't go - I - I - not really at Christmas 'cos the maids done it, but this was the work you see, during the day we - I had to do. But - well I only stayed down there two years because the house was in a wood. And - because - they told me
 I'd have to have someone dawn there to look after me when the - when I was having this baby. We couldn't - well, we couldn't get no one so we moved. That was three years after I was married. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you work again after that?
\par MC:\tab Not after I had me baby, no.
\par I:\tab That was the last job you had?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Oh, I've had jobs since, in between, yes.
\par I:\tab The same kind of jobs?
\par MC:\tab Yes, housework. Oh yes. I've done - no end of jobs for different people, and still keep doing a little. Yes. Washing, I've took washing in for all sorts - Big - bigger people than what we are ourselves like. Yes. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Did your husband remain a gardener or did he have other jobs?
\par MC:\tab No, he - he's up the nurseries. In the nurseries.
\par I:\tab He moved up from the nurseries and he became a nurseryman?
\par MC:\tab Yes. He worked - worked for the nurseries.
\par I:\tab And he stayed there for the rest of his life?
\par MC:\tab Rest of his life, yes. Yes. Yes my son - that's the Stanton nurseries, well they've done away with now, my son - 
my younger son - eldest son, went to these nurseries, fourteen on the Friday and he started on the Mon - the Monday, and he was there - until they give 'em up, about twenty-eight years, that's only one job.
\par I:\tab What's he done since then?
\par MC:\tab He's working - with me other son - what they call the bacon factory.
\par I:\tab Bacon factory?
\par MC:\tab Well they call it the bacon factory, that's - that's in Stansted. They do a lot - sell a lot of the bacon that goes round miles and miles.
\par I:\tab What does he do there?
\par MC:\tab Well, they - they have groceries as well but he's sort of a factory. And -
\par I:\tab Do you know what kind of job he has there though?
\par MC:\tab Well do - mostly do cutting up bacon or something like that now, the eldest one. And the youngest one, well he's there, he's sort of under-manager, so I've got two sons on the same - same - just - sort of job really.
\par I:\tab Under-manager?
\par MC:\tab Yes, well - the youngest one is. But the eldest one is just ordinary. Yes.
\par I:\tab How did the youngest one start off then?
\par MC:\tab Well 'cos he - well he - he - he was in the factory helping well I suppose the - he got on and they -
\par I:\tab He got promoted?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What's your middle one done then?
\par MC:\tab Middle one, he's up the airport, been up there since he come out the army.
\par I:\tab What does he do there?
\par MC:\tab Up the - at the airport? Well I don't know, they call it on the light. You - you know, they have to have these lights to guide the planes in, well he's about with those lights, that's his job and -
\par I:\tab Making sure they're in repair and so on?
\par MC:\tab Yes, been there - as I tell you, ever since - he come out of the army. Yes. Yes. He's still there.
\par I:\tab Do your daughter-in-laws work?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What are they doing?
\par MC:\tab 
Eldest one does a - eldest daughter-in-law she does house - housework. She's been doing a job I think for about ten years. And second one - she goes about twice a week. Think it's twice a week. Oh youngest one don't 'cos she's got young - young children.

\par I:\tab Have either of them done other jobs before they were married?
\par MC:\tab Well youngest - me youngest daughter-in-law, she used to be a - one of the head typists in the factory at Stortford, she did. Second one - where did she work - Harlow, Spirella factory.
\par I:\tab What was she doing there, do you know?
\par MC:\tab Make things there in - in the factory, well that's still there as far as I know. Yes.
\par I:\tab Sort of machinist?
\par MC:\tab Yes. And the eldest one - ah she was out doing housework. Yes. Yes, she did housework. Yes. And the eldest one, well she can do anything.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me what your brothers and sisters did, I think you said all the brothers started on farms?
\par MC:\tab On farms, yes.
\par I:\tab Did they all stay at that?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Well I'm afraid there was one - well, no, the youngest one now he's on what they call the council, Borough Council.
\par I:\tab On the roads?
\par MC:\tab Yes. The second one, well he's retired. I mean he's turned sixty-five but he does part time on the farm. Oh the eldest one, of course he don't do anything at all, 'cos he
's eighty-one. But he - he done his ~ over fifty years on the farm. You know, they get these long - they give you certificate for being on the farms all those years at the - Essex Show. You've heard of that surely? Well he was one of 'em two years ago. In
 fact I've still got his photo there, but he - he's finished now. The other one, he - well he was on a farm but I can't - he died. Last year. But they were all on the farm. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did their wives do any jobs, or did they marry?
\par MC:\tab No, the one what died, h
e - he hadn't been married. Oh me youngest brother was, died years ago. When the - babe - one baby was only two. Well he's never married again so - she wouldn't have any - no, the eldest one of course she's - she'd - eighty the same as me - brother. She d
on't do nothing.
\par I:\tab She had worked when she was younger I meant?
\par MC:\tab Well she - what, the eldest brother's wife, well she - she originated from - London, she was evacuee, so I don't really know what she did do. 'Cos me eldest brother's - first wife died. We
ll she - was one like me, worked - done - housework, but she died rather young, then me brother got married again to this one and she was evacuee, but I don't know what she did. And then he married her. And - we - brother next to me, well I don't think hi
s wife does anything. No, I don't think she does much since she's been married. No.
\par I:\tab The first wife, when you say housework, you mean she was a living in, in service living in?
\par MC:\tab Not after she's married, but before she was married, like the same as I.
\par I:\tab And then she carried on afterwards?
\par MC:\tab Yes, doing a bit - of course they never had any family. Well they haven't got any now so - no. As I said - I said I only had four brothers, the second one as I say he's gone - well he'd been in a home all these yea
rs. Yes. And - one - the next one to me - don't think his wife, I don't think she's ever been out to work. Not her. And the youngest one of course she - well his wife died so - she's never done any. He didn't do anything. But - she was - in - housework li
ke myself, me youngest brother's wife, that's how he picked up with her, by coming to - Stansted. Yes. So we all sort of - in the family of housework if you know what I mean. Yes.
\par I:\tab Your sisters all started like that?
\par MC:\tab My sisters did.
\par I:\tab Have any of your sisters done anything different in fact?
\par MC:\tab No, what - no, me sisters, they always in - in - what we called service 'til they got married. All of 'em. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they all then go back and do a bit of charring afterwards?
\par MC:\tab Well if they hadn't got no family. Otherwise they might have done a day here and a day there, but - they never did anything else. If it was work that was indoors. See.
\par I:\tab Did they all marry?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me what their husbands did?
\par MC:\tab Well me eldest sister's husband, he was - well he worked on the railway. On the railway 'till he retired.
\par I:\tab What did he do on the railway?
\par MC:\tab Well I don't know, what they call plate laying or something. 'Ti1 he - in the end he was on - what they called Southend Water Works. That was at 
- Langford and Maldon, that way, you know that part don't you. Well that's where me sister lived, that's where she died. And the second one - the one I stayed with, he died rather he didn't live long after coming out the First World War, well he - he work
ed on Bishop Stortford Council, as far as I - he did. And the next -
\par I:\tab That's the third isn't it?
\par MC:\tab That's the third, then you see the next sister, well her husband - he was - he was on a farm prac - all his life.
\par I:\tab Round here?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Well at Broxted,
 yes. Of course he's been dead for several years, but that - that - and he was retired, but that was his work, on the farm. And then - the - sister next to me elder, her husband was on the railway. He was - well, not guard, what do you call - next to the 
guard?
\par I:\tab Well there's a fireman?
\par MC:\tab Oh something - there - he used to go - Clacton to London, then they moved to Col - Colchester and he used to go from Colchester to London, he kept on 'til he - he done his forty-five.
\par I:\tab He was on the train, not the guard you say?
\par MC:\tab No, I don't - not the guard I don't think he was.
\par I:\tab He wasn't a ticket collector?
\par MC:\tab No, he - no, he went on the train. Could be fireman I suppose.
\par I:\tab He was up in the engine you mean?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Anyway he travelled as I said from Clacton t
o London, and then they moved to Colchester and then that was that 'til he retired, he done forty-five years. 'Cos they give him a gold watch. But now I - now I mean he's - turned seventy, he's seventy-three, I - I don't - I think he's just - I don't know
 
what me sister said he did, sweep the school up or something like - just a little light job. And then the sister next to me below me - well her husband's retired and he was on a farm 'til be - he'd been - used to farm and then he went - at Stortford brewe
ry. And now he's - he's retired he just does half a day gardening.
\par I:\tab What was has doing at the brewery?
\par MC:\tab Bottling up beer as far as I know. Yes.
\par I:\tab It's very interesting to see how a family -
\par MC:\tab Yes, the - the - I mean me family - well you can say they
've all sort of - are farm men, really. That was most of their work. I suppose they've done a few odd jobs I mean since they retired, but actually really from their childhood was farming. Yes. Work on a farm. Yes.
\par I:\tab And long service too?
\par MC:\tab Yes, me broth
er. Yes. I could have got his photo and showed you, but there's a photo - I had it. That was - thinks it's two years ago. Yes. And he still lives down - on - in the farm cottage now. Yes. Between - don't know, between Broxted and Great Eastham. Yes. Yes.

\par I:\tab When you were at school did your mother or father ever go up to the school and meet the teachers and so on?
\par MC:\tab Well they didn't have what they called teachers day, parents day, not - not much then but - she went when - when th
ere was fresh one started, that is if she was all right, if not me sister took us. She met them then. Well I did think - I think she met them occasionally 'cos - we had to go up my school to - she said to have 'em vaccinated - every so often that they use
d
 to come and vaccinate these children. But - 'cos they - see we only had what we called a schoolmaster - and his wife, they used to call her governess, and his daughter was the teacher. All in one family. And then we had another teacher at the little vill
age post office. That's all the teachers we had. See?
\par I:\tab Did your mother and father take an interest in what you were doing at school?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab I mean ask you how you were getting on?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Oh yes. 'Cos I - well I was one of them what got on too - too well. Yes. Now my sister often laughs about it.
\par I:\tab Did they - before you went to school did your mother and father teach you anything?
\par MC:\tab Well not actually, I think we just picked up off the others.
\par I:\tab You picked up, you mean to count and so on?
\par MC:\tab 
Yes. I mean she learned us the Lord's Prayer and - and that. But we had to say that every night, I always had to learn that. Yes, poor old girl. We used to sit there with our hands in her lap like that. Yes. Oh yes. I mean little things like that she lea
rnt us. Taught us. But - other - like actual sort of school things we picked up off one another, 'cos rather - one child'd want a pencil as well as the other. But we had slates then. You remember slate - oh no, you wouldn't you know. Slates they called 'e
m
. Well in fact I've got one here now, I bought it when I went on a - well I won it in the raffle at - when I went to Clacton on holiday, slates and - crayons and - slate pencils, that's what we used to have. And in our village school there was like _ blac
kboards but they weren't boards actually, be - I suppose they must have been - all put round the wall. We had to do - lessons and reading on these walls, see but - of course they don't do nothing of that now. No. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father take any interest in cricket?
\par MC:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Or football?
\par MC:\tab No. No. No, he didn't no. No. Fact I don't think we had footballs and cricket as go and play what the children used to play on their own.
\par I:\tab There was no sort of betting possible?
\par MC:\tab No. No, not - not when I was a gir
l, no, no. That's - that weren't - all has been started since - 'cos I mean we used to have a tennis ball, play rounders. Yes. Boys had an old cricket bat made out of bit of wood. Play on their own, but - we didn't actually have cricket matches and footba
l
l matches at school. You just had this between yourselves like. The only thing I remember we had was a big swing in the playground. That was - and we - we used to sit down on the path - playground, that was tarmac, the girls, play marbles. Five -' five ma
rbles.
\par I:\tab Did - if your mother and father actually weren't working how would they spend their time, did they have a way of enjoying themselves?
\par MC:\tab Well no, 'cos I mean - apart from that they was always working mare or less 'cos I mean - as I say me father 
didn't get home - well by the time he had his meal - and - and got - and had the mornings wood in as he called it, that - that was - eyeing was - sort of going wasn't it. Yes. Oh no, there was no sport. Didn't get a paper only once a week.
\par I:\tab They didn't have friends who would drop in to see them?
\par MC:\tab Well - only their relations.
\par I:\tab Just relations?
\par MC:\tab Yes, or perhaps there'd be a - one of the rich people call in occasionally, but - my mother never done any entertaining -
\par I:\tab I mean just dropping in for a cup of tea or something like that?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Oh - yes, well might to drop - yes, they'd do that in the dinner times sometimes one odd lady used to pop in and see mother, but never what I call done much entertaining. 'Cos she hadn't got enough - she couldn't c
ope with us let alone any more. No.
\par I:\tab Did your father have friends at work though?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, he'd have -
\par I:\tab But he wouldn't bring them home?
\par MC:\tab No, he was a sort of quiet sort of a man really.
\par I:\tab Did your mother ever go out to visit anybody?
\par MC:\tab 
No. Neither of 'em - no, not to say visit, no. You know, only got a little shop down the village, she used to go to shopping, but - perhaps she'd go to Henham, that's the next village. But not the towns, you could walk there and back. See father used to t
o go market every Thursday but - that was about all. And that was for the master. Of course. Yes.
\par I:\tab You say there were relations?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How many relations were there sort of close at hand?
\par MC:\tab Oh got several auntie's and uncles.
\par I:\tab In the village?
\par MC:\tab In the village. Yes. And one was what they used to call a snob. Mend shoes. Yes. Mended the shoes, Uncle Arthur as they call him. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were they on your mother's side or your father's side?
\par MC:\tab Mother's side. Oh there was one on me father's side but s
he was right out - older than me father and she died before. We did visit her I know, especially after me father died. Yes. But I mean when my father stopped at home first I was only eight. Well of course he didn't ever work for two years before he died, 
so I mean I was only eight then. Yes.
\par I:\tab Your mother wouldn't go around to call on these sisters or brothers of hers then?
\par MC:\tab Not very often, perhaps she might slip out if the weather was nice, take the child and that with her but then I mean she had to be home to sort of get the tea and that.
\par I:\tab And they wouldn't come round to see her?
\par MC:\tab Well, they might pop round occasionally you know as they went down the shop as they call it. Used to come round just to have five minute's chat but - you see mother hadn't got all the time to spare really.
\par I:\tab So you didn't see much of them as a child?
\par MC:\tab Well, not a lot. Well you - we see 'em if we went past the cot - the place where they lived you know.
\par I:\tab So you'd just say hello and have a chat?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You don't ever remember having a sort of evening get together?
\par MC:\tab Oh no.
\par I:\tab With singing or something?
\par MC:\tab Oh no. Nothing like - nothing - nothing of that, no. None of that at all. No. No. Oh no.
\par I:\tab People often say that the neighbours helped more in these days?
\par MC:\tab 
Well I think she'd got one or two good neighbours, 'cos you - that helped her, which she was - most grateful for, 'cos I - I know they allowed her - she had to pay this woman to come in and do the washing, well that was one whole day. And then she'd 
often pop - pop in and say, well I'm going down the shop Mrs Wright, is there anything you want? Can I help, do anything like that. See, 'cos she didn't get no time to spare, there was so many children round her. No.
\par I:\tab What sort of ways do you think neighbours would help at that time?
\par MC:\tab Well - well I don't think they actually came and done a lot as far as that goes, 'cos mothe
r'd got this other - daughter home, but they'd pop in and say, well if there's anything - I can do or - you know - now, and that, but you see - mother hadn't got anything sort of to give 'em in return so - so she didn't like - to - sort of impose on 'em r
eally.
\par I:\tab Would they lend things?
\par MC:\tab Well they - yes, they did borrow from one another it is true, yes. 'Specially if you was short of bread. I mean when the baker comes - only comes round twice a week well it's a bit difficult sometimes to know quite how 
much the children was going to eat in't it? Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab When they came round would she give them a cup of tea?
\par MC:\tab Mother did, yes. Oh yes. And that was - mother used to say - give it away - give it away willingly, she'd say, the Lord will reward you. I r
emember her say - give it away willingly she said, the Lord will reward you. We didn't know what she meant. Yes, the Lord'll reward us. But - but that is true in a way, if you do these things - it does come back to you, 'cos I found that out myself. Yes. 
There's some of these good old sayings are really true. Yes. Yes, they are. I - I found it out anyway.
\par I:\tab You've been helped a lot yourself?
\par MC:\tab Yes. And mother used - any of these - and - old people used to come round the door, these old tramps we used to 
call, they used to say, can you give us a drop of water in this tin? And mother'd go and boil it - give 'em some boiled water, they come back a few minutes after, have you got any tea to put in it. Well you got all those round - round the village of Broxt
e
d - well I suppose they went _ other other places as well, and - this washerwoman used to say to mother, well - oh you are a silly Mrs Wright, she'd say, keep giving that to they, she'd say, you've got all them children. She said, oh I know that, she said
,
 they've got more than what you have got. She says, well I ain't supposed to know that, she'll say, what they've got, what they haven't got, she said. Then she said that's my mother used to say, give it away willingly, she said, the Lord will reward you o
n
e day. See? But - which she would, she'd give them the last piece of bread she'd got if she - if they asked for a piece. Yes. 'Cos you often got that round Broxted. Oh yes. Well - what I call these old rough ones what used to sleep anywhere, come round wi
th a little old tin in a - bit of string for a handle, and then - they'd go down the road and then come back and say, have you got a drop of tea, or crust of bread.
\par I:\tab Would they be selling things then?
\par MC:\tab Not - not these old tramps wouldn't. No.
\par I:\tab Did you have some people travelling round?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. Selling pegs and all, yes, always round the door.
\par I:\tab Those were different?
\par MC:\tab They were a little different - but so - she got so - so she didn't go to the door sometimes 'cos she could never get rid of them. No, you couldn't get rid of 'em.
\par I:\tab Do you remember cheapjacks selling clothes?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of things did they have then?
\par MC:\tab Well, cheapjack lamp, I remember my mother had little old tiny lamp, weren't no bigger than that. Little old bras
s thing, and we - wick weren't so big as round as a - pencil. And - and so that was cheapjack's lamp, yes. Yes. We'd have that sometimes to go to bed with if we hadn't got a candle. Had to take candles to bed. Oh I wonder what the children really think of
 
that now if they had to go back to the days when you did. I mean you go one room to another, you put a light on, we go out of one room we're in the dark. And if you hadn't got a candle handy you got to come - push your way around to find where you'd left 
t
he candle. And - I mean you - mother used to say, be careful of them matches, where you're putting them, but I mean - get throwing the matches down well you soon have a fire wouldn't you. 'Cos if you took the candle upstairs she took the matches away from
 you. So if it went out - you was left in the dark.
\par I:\tab Were you frightened of the dark?
\par MC:\tab No, we got used to it, I mean we sort of brought up in the dark if you know what I mean. But -
\par I:\tab You weren't frightened of ghosts then?
\par MC:\tab Well we didn't like that 'cos when we - if we had to go t the toilet it was half way down - across down there. Had to take a candle in a lantern.
\par I:\tab Down the garden?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Two of us used to go - together and say come - come on with me. And then half - you get half way down the
re and the candle blew out. In the lantern. Little you must have seen these little lanterns surely, something like - with - with a candle - the little windows round the side and you had - handle on the top. And if they got the least little bit of draught 
o
ut would go the candle. Then we'd be stuck. I mean that's dreadful in't it. When you've got a family and an - and a - a toilet down the garden, ain't got nowhere else to go. Well I mean the children now go - well they won't move out of one room into the o
ther so - without going out half way down the garden before they can get to a toilet.
\par I:\tab Would you say that you were one of the poorest families in the village?
\par MC:\tab Well, I - I think there's one or two nearly, but with - I suppose they took pity more or less on us because we was such a large family you see of us. They weren't quite - I think mother's was the largest family - then.
\par I:\tab But there were some people who were poorer?
\par MC:\tab Oh they got - they'd got about seven or eight but I think mother had the most. Yes. Mother had the most.
\par I:\tab Were there in fact any other families you would have said were as poor as you?
\par MC:\tab Would help us, yes.
\par I:\tab Why were these other ones poorer do you think?
\par MC:\tab Well they thought it was - I don't know, their fathers was on he farm the same as us, perhaps they didn't manage as well as what my mother did, they was more - me mother as I say was such a good manager.
\par I:\tab She was noted for that then?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab You were quite proud of that as children?
\par MC:\tab Yes, and I mean in her needlework and that, anything like that. Oh she'd sit up all night and get these things done what she wanted.
\par I:\tab When you say the others didn't manage well, what sort of ways would they be bad managers?
\par MC:\tab Well perhaps them - perhaps their - fathers drank or something you see. But - no, I think we was - really as I - as I could see one - you know, the best of the poorest if you know what I mean.
\par I:\tab Best of the poorest you think?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Best of the poorest. Well anyway she did keep us clean. Yes.
\par I:\tab Some families were dirty then?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, well we did - we were kept clean. Too clean sometimes.
\par I:\tab Were there some of the children in the school who were dirty?
\par MC:\tab Well there was one or two, yes.
\par I:\tab Just one or two?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Not the lot?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were children like that looked down on by the others?
\par MC:\tab Well, sometimes they did, other children looked down on 'em, then they start fighting coming home and - yes.
\par I:\tab What would your mother think of a family where the children were dirty for instance?
\par MC:\tab Well she used to say to us now don't you go and say nothing to that child, she can't help it. Well of course she couldn't. I mean you couldn't put the blame on the child could you?
\par I:\tab What about the mother, would she have anything to do with the mother?
\par MC:\tab Well I suppose she - spoke - if they lived near, spoke to 'em and that but - as I said, mother didn't get out a lot. I do.
\par I:\tab But you were really brought up to feel that you were a bit superior through being clean?
\par MC:\tab Well we were clean and too clean as I said 'cos we wouldn't - she wouldn't let us sit and put your feet round up - and washing us every morning. We had to go through the morning. Was - you get - she'd have a hairp
in and when you had a - and dig that in your ears. Well we - I - well I tell you, we didn't half have to through it sometimes. Yes. The bowl - you had to have it on the table, to wash, 'cos nowhere else to go. Get a kettle of boiling water, hot water so t
here was enough for all of us to wash. Mind you we was done every night so we didn't have much to do in the morning. Yes.
\par I:\tab What was the attitude to swearing at that time?
\par MC:\tab No, we daren't say - mother never swore, occasionally me father did but you see we was in bed, but we didn't swear. And I don't know. No.
\par I:\tab If there was a family where there was swearing would that be looked down on?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes. But I mean - take it in the country more or less the farm workers do swear, 'cos they - they swear at the animals more or less.
\par I:\tab But not inside the house?
\par MC:\tab Yes. When that comes out don't it. Yes. I mean you wouldn't get many farm - farm men on a farm what don't swear. 'Cos I've heard 'em say, the - the horses there'll make you swear. Yes.
\par I:\tab Would you say there were some of the ordinary families in the village who were rather better off than you?
\par MC:\tab Yes. They - they would give mother some things I've heard her say, like clothing and that and then she could - if I'd didn't do for one she could cut i
t down for another, 'cos she was good with a needle, then she hadn't got a machine. That's what I said, that's one of the reasons she had to sit up half of the night needlework.
\par I:\tab What would their fathers be doing there, what sort of jobs would they have?
\par MC:\tab What - the father's father?
\par I:\tab If it was an ordinary family but slightly better off I was wondering why that would be?
\par MC:\tab Well I don't know what it was, there was nothing much in Broxted for 'em to do. I don't know if they went anywhere further to do anything.
\par I:\tab There wouldn't be a sort of blacksmith or somebody like that?
\par MC:\tab Not - not - Stansted there was one but weren't actually one at Brox - we had a mule. That was done away with when I was a little girl, where they ground the corn. 'Cos many tim
es I've been up there have to get a peck of maize. Got a peck of maize and then come home eating them, that's chickens food. Yes. Mill, what else was there in Stansted - in Broxted. Oh nothing really. I mean how they done - one or two of 'em did alert of 
building they'd have to go - really sort of to Dunmow, or they'd come and fetch them, there wasn't anything really much else. Not in the village. I mean postman come from - outside the village. There was just the little post office. And the vicarage.

\par I:\tab It's a very scattered sort of place isn't it?
\par MC:\tab That is. You been through it? Well I mean we lived this end, and there's all ends in't it, there's Brick End, Woodleys End, Browns End, Javel End, well we lived at Brick End and Church End is up the other end.
 So we had to walk from Brick End through what I call the village to get to Brick End - to Church End school. Yes.
\par I:\tab Is your cottage still there?
\par MC:\tab Well the cottage is where mother actually had one, then the Lady Warrick had one made into two, we had tw
o. Then there was another one that joined on the end, that was like three - three cottages altogether. And now it's all one. They done a lot of that in Broxted, they done - different people after we - sort of was getting growed up come in and bought these
 
cottages, which were two, and made 'em into one. Thatched places. There's a thatched - little thatched cottage I had when I first married, a beautiful place now. Yes. Really beautiful. Yes. There's not half so many cottages now as there was because I said
 one's made into two.
\par I:\tab You were talking about your mother and father's friends, would you say that they - that your mother's friends were mainly women and your father's his work mates or did they sort of share the same ones?
\par MC:\tab More or less shared the sa
me ones, yes, yes. 'Cos I think one - one or two of 'em were father's relations on the farm same as him you see. Yes. One farm there - up that end, well that was - that was on the way, as you know, to Henham, that's where me father - worked and there's on
e
 what we called - Brick End, Broxted Hall, that's where me brothers worked. See some was - somebody was on one, 'cos they employed - employed about - some of 'em had about a dozen, which now don't have none hardly. Yes. Well that - that - that's all there
 was in Broxted, I've never heard of anything else going.
\par I:\tab Your family had been there a long time?
\par MC:\tab Was all born there. Me mother's people were born there. Yes. Yes, mother's people. I remember me mother's father - huge great old big man, they used to call him Smalls. Because he was so big they called him Smalls. Yes.
\par I:\tab He worked on the farm too then?
\par MC:\tab As far as I can remember, of course I mean he was old then.
\par I:\tab Did you see a bit of him then?
\par MC:\tab 
I did, I - I remember him dying. Yes. Remember him dying. 'Cos more or less -nearly all people died at home that time of day. Yes. And I remember me granny dying. Me mother's mother, I don't remember me - father's - mother or father. They was dead before 
I can remember.
\par I:\tab Did they take you round to see them after they'd died then?
\par MC:\tab Well - I remember going down with me mother when she went to see me - she - mother lived through here and she just lived across the road there. I said take us - she took us w
ith her. We had to, there was nobody home to stay at home with us, she had to take us with her. Couldn't leave us home alone. No. And she only lived in a little tiny cottage, I can remember that.
\par I:\tab You remember the old man?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he talk to you at all about anything?
\par MC:\tab No, he was an old devil I've heard me mother say. He was one what drank. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember any sort of stories he used to tell then?
\par MC:\tab Well they - I know my - I've heard me mother say he used to come home and hide - 
home and hide his money. Because he wouldn't give to me - me grandmother you see. Me mother's mother. Because he used to like - like his drink. I've heard her say he used to before he went in, and yet he'd be half drunk, he used to hide in the fetch in th
e house and he'd hide it before he come in. Oh he was an old devil he was. I've heard me mother say so. Yes.
\par I:\tab What else did he do?
\par MC:\tab Well I mean he wouldn't give me mother no money - me grandmother no not her - no money. No. There was one or two of 'em 
like that in Braxted. Yes. Used - as soon as they got the money they used to go and - spend it on drink, then the wives had to go without. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he have a great big beard?
\par MC:\tab Yes. Picture him now really. Here, my sister's got a photo of him, he look
s - 'ever such a kind old gentleman in his face. As my brother said, you can't go by people's looks can you? No. No you can't. Well you meet people and say, oh ain't she nice, well they don't know anything about her really. No. No, may think my mother's o
n
e of the really old - old - good old fashioned type in the village of Brox - and me sister takes after her. I've got one sister still lives there, and she's had twelve children I told you. Yes. And my word, talk about she - talk about mother being clean, 
I
 think she's - well, you know, can't say she's no cleaner but she's spotless. Yes. Yes. Nobody need - and she talks to everybody the same, the vicar, the doctor or anybody. Yes. She don't - serve 'em all alike she'll say. Yes. So she does. When the doctor
 goes in to her he'll say, morning Daisy. Yes.
